{In Caro-Kann Part 1, we covered the classical and solid 3...Bf5, a long-standing mainstay of the opening, offering Black a reliable setup with rich strategic ideas. But modern preparation is never static—players must be ready to expand their repertoire with dynamic alternatives. That’s why in Part 4, we take a different path: 3...c5!?, the immediate counterstrike in the center. This sharper, more double-edged approach gives Black excellent counterplay from the start. Why include both 3...Bf5 and 3...c5? Simple: flexibility and surprise value. While 3...Bf5 remains the classical choice, the early c5-break has gained momentum at the highest levels. With this database, you’ll be ready to handle 3.e5 from both a classical and a dynamic perspective, adapting your approach based on your opponent and tournament needs.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 (4. Ne2 {and other sidelines are not dangerous, but we will analyze them in Chapter 11.}) (4. c3 {Positional line, recommended by Giri. We will study it in Chapter 10.}) (4. Nf3 {White's second main move.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 (5. Qxd4 $5 {is extremely popular nowadays.} Nc6 6. Qf4 f6 $5 {will be my recommendation in Chapter 1. Instead of studying the mainstream 6...e6, with 400+ games and heavy theory, I suggest 10...f6—a more ambitious and fresh approach. It has only been played 10 times, including once by me in 2024, when I defeated Alexander Grischuk with this line.}) 5... Nc6 6. Nxc6 (6. c4 $5 {Chapter 3.}) (6. Bb5 $5 {Chapter 3.}) 6... bxc6 7. Bd3 {This is the most common continuation, and we will analyze it in Chapter 2. I have a lot of experience here, having faced this variation many times in both classical and rapid games}) 4... e6 {In this variation, we often get French-like structures, but with a key difference.In the French, you follow standard moves but you have a long-term strategic risk. Here, once past move 10 with good preparation, we have full control and no long-term problems.} 5. Nf3 (5. Be3 {White’s attempt to hold onto the pawn is not very popular nowadays, and for good reason. We will study this in Chapter 4.}) (5. a3 {very popular line. We will study it in Chapter 5.}) (5. Bd3 $5 {tricky move order. We will study it in Chapter 7.}) (5. c3 {this move is very popular at the high level. Chapter 8.}) (5. Qg4 {An important move to consider, as we can no longer play Bxc5. We will examine this in Chapter 9.}) 5... Bxc5 6. Bd3 {In my opinion, this is White’s most logical try—not necessarily the best, but the most natural. We will analyze it in Chapter 6, where I’ll introduce a fresh solution that cuts through a lot of heavy theory.} *

