{[%evp 0,20,18,31,57,41,41,49,53,31,25,3,3,7,27,28,18,26,9,9,9,14,20]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 (4. c3 {A sideline that has become very popular nowadays. White usually chooses this move if, in his repertoire against 3... Bf5, he continues with 4.Nf3 e6 5.Be2 c5 6.c3. By playing 4.c3 against our 3... c5, White aims to transpose into the same setup he uses against 3...Bf5, allowing him to prepare just one system against the Caro-Kann instead of studying multiple variations.} Nc6 5. Be2 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Rc8g4] White's most interesting move order, and it was suggested by GM Anish Giri. By starting with 5.Be2, White prevents Black's Bg4 options.} (5. Nf3 {[%cal Gc8g4] harmless move order because Black can now develop the bishop to g4.} cxd4 ({But not} 5... Bg4 $6 {immediately because of} 6. dxc5 $1 $14) 6. cxd4 Bg4 $1 {A lot of games here, but Black is already fine.}) 5... cxd4 $5 {My recommendation. I like it because it leads to a very simple equality, without the need to memorize many lines.} 6. cxd4 Qb6 $5 {[%csl Rd4] immediately putting pressure against d4.} 7. Nc3 $1 {critical move.} ({After the natural} 7. Nf3 {Black has} Bg4 $132 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8e7] e6-Nge7 and no problem. Maybe it's even easier to play this from the Black's side.}) 7... Qxd4 {only 10 games here, but this is the simplest solution against the 4.c3 Nc6 5.Be2!? tricky line.} 8. Nxd5 Qxd1+ 9. Bxd1 Rb8 $1 {This is the critical position, but there are only 4 games. The details of this endgame can be analyzed in Chapter 10.}) (4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 (5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qf4 {The topic of this chapter.} f6 $5 {This is what Alexey prepared some months ago, in the Russian Final against GM Grischuk, it is a very interesting move.} 7. Nc3 {This is probably White's most critical move.} (7. Bb5 {Grischuk didn't spend too much time, and played the most logical move.} g5 $1 {The idea is to play against White's queen.} 8. Qa4 {Grischuk's choice.} g4 {The best move.} 9. Nd4 {was played in the game.} (9. Bxc6+ $146 bxc6 10. Nd4 fxe5 11. Qxc6+ {How to play with Black?} Qd7 $1 {The best move.} (11... Bd7 $4 {Don't play this move, because after} 12. Qxd5 $18 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gd5h5,Re5d4] Black cannot capture on d4.}) 12. Qxa8 exd4 $11 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg8f6,Ge8g8] And Black plays for compensation.}) 9... fxe5 10. Nxc6 {White's most logical move.} bxc6 11. Bxc6+ Bd7 $11) 7... a6 $1 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Rf1b5] Important move to stop Bb5.} (7... e6 $2 {would be a serious mistake.} 8. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Ge5f6,Gb5c7] And Black's position is critical.}) 8. exf6 {don't be afraid of this structure.} Nxf6 9. Bd3 e6 $11 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gf8d6] The position is just normal, and French players know that this structure is okay for Black, also the queen on f4 is not fantastic here.}) 5... Nc6 {The mainline is 6.Nxc6, but White also has other options.} 6. Nxc6 {The mainline. Nowadays, this one is very popular at all levels.} (6. c4 {Important line.} dxc4 $5 {Practical solution and our main recommendation. Here, you just need to remember one important line, and not a lot of forced variations like in the 6...e6 line.} 7. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 bxc6 9. Bxc4 Bf5 $1 {[%csl Cc6][%cal Bg8e7,Be7d5,Ge7e6] At first glance, this endgame might seem slightly unpleasant due to the c6 and a7 pawns. However, in reality, it is completely equal. Our pawn on c6 is actually useful, as it helps us execute the key maneuver Ne7-Nd5.}) (6. Bb5 {Rare line, but White has some tricky ideas here.} Bd7 7. Nxc6 Bxc6 $1 ({but not} 7... bxc6 $6 8. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Rd7] because White is playing the 6.Nc6 line, where our bishop is misplaced on d7 (no a5-Ba6 plan).}) 8. Bd3 {only 8 games, but this is an important position.} (8. Bxc6+ {doesn't make sense.} bxc6 9. O-O e6 $11 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7g6,Bf8e7,Be8g8] we are playing the 6.Nxc6 line, where we don't even need to spend time for a5-Ba6 to exchange the bishops.}) 8... d4 $1 {[%csl Bd4] important move.}) 6... bxc6 7. Bd3 {In this chapter we are going to check this line.} e6 {Normal move, the best. Now White has only 2 serious options: 0-0 or Nd2.} 8. O-O {The main line, and now important moment for Black: Ne7 or a5.} a5 {Most practical move order because we exclude the 8...Ne7 9.Re1 Karjakin line.} 9. Nd2 {Logical continuation.} Ne7 {This is the main position, that can be reached from both move orders.} 10. Nf3 {The main line.} (10. Qe2 {White stops Ba6, now important move:} Ng6 $1 {[%cal Rg6f4] With tempo.} 11. Nf3 Be7 12. g3 {[%cal Gh2h4] White prepares h4.} O-O 13. h4 f6 $1 {important move.}) 10... Ba6 {It's very important for us to exchange the bishops.} 11. Bxa6 {The most common move.} Rxa6 12. c4 {A lot of strong players went for this position.} Ng6 {The best option.} 13. Qe2 {White's most common continuation.} Ra8 {everybody plays 13...d4, which is good, but it's not necessary to sacrifice a pawn.}) 4... e6 5. Nf3 (5. Be3 {The most concrete move, White wants to keep the extra pawn.} Nd7 6. Bb5 {Critical and most interesting.} (6. Nf3 {Positional line, but harmless.} Bxc5 7. Bxc5 Nxc5 $11 {We have an improved version of the French.}) 6... Ne7 7. Bd4 $1 {Best move, according to the engine.} (7. Nf3 {Most common way.} Nf5 {Good move to attack the e3 bishop.} 8. b4 {Necessary move.} a6 $5 {I think the inclusion is useful for Black.} 9. Ba4 a5 {This is Black's counterplay idea.} 10. c3 Nxe3 11. fxe3 g6 $132 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8g7] We want to develop the bishop on the long diagonal, to put pressure on e5 and later c3.}) 7... Nf5 {Very solid choice, and also simpler to play, in my opinion.} 8. c3 {The most logical.} Be7 {Finish development.} 9. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2b3] The best, to defend the pawn with the knight.} O-O 10. Nb3 {The most logical.} b6 $1 {Very important moment, we don't need to recapture material, but play this typical move for compensation.} 11. c6 {Logical move.} (11. cxb6 {White had to do something with the pawn.} Nxd4 {Good intermezzo.} 12. Nxd4 Qxb6 $11 {Black has just compensation.}) 11... Nc5 12. Nf3 Qc7 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gc7c6] a6-Qxc6 next.}) (5. Bd3 $5 {Tricky move order.} Nd7 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Re5][%cal Gd7e5,Gd7c5]} ({Don't play} 5... Bxc5 $2 {because after} 6. Qg4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rg7] Black doesn't have a good reaction to defend g7.}) 6. Nf3 {White must defend e5.} Nxc5 {[%csl Gc5,Yd3][%cal Yc5d3]} 7. O-O {Most common continuation.} Nxd3 {We want to see how White recaptures before deciding on the best way to continue our development.} 8. Qxd3 {I am more concerned about 8.Qxd3.} Ne7 $11) (5. c3 {a lot of strong players used this line.} Nd7 $1 {we play in the same spirit of the 5.Bd3 line.} (5... Bxc5 $2 {most natural and common move, but it's a mistake, and White uses the same idea of the 5.Bd3 line.} 6. Qg4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rg7] no good reaction for Black.}) 6. Nf3 Bxc5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] corret recapture.} (6... Nxc5 $6 {[%csl Gf1] this was good when White's bishop was on d3, but not here.}) 7. Nbd2 {only good move for White.} (7. Bd3 $6 {now White is not in time to consolidate:} f6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] important move.}) 7... Qb6 $1 $11 {[%csl Gb6] important move: we don't allow White to develop in the desired way. just draw.} 8. Qe2 {only move.} Qa6 {safest continuation.} 9. Qxa6 (9. Qd1 Qb6 $11 {just draw.}) 9... bxa6 $11 {[%csl Ca6,Ca7] our pawns are good, don't worry.}) (5. a3 $5 Bxc5 $1 6. Qg4 (6. b4 Be7 7. Nf3 f6) 6... Ne7 $1 {We sacrifice the g7 pawn, and the concrete lines can be seen in Chapter 9.}) (5. Qg4 {White provokes h5.} h5 6. Qf4 Bxc5 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. Nf3 f6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] very important move.} 9. Qg3 $1 {important prophylactic move.} (9. O-O $6 g5 $1 10. Bg6+ Kf8 $19) 9... Qc7 10. O-O g5 $5 11. exf6 Qxg3 12. hxg3 g4 $11 {Equal endgame.}) 5... Bxc5 6. Bd3 {This is an important variation.} (6. a3 f6 $1 7. b4 Be7 $1 8. Bb2 {mainline.} a5 $1 {Better to start with a5, because anyway it is useful move.} 9. b5 {Most played move.} Nd7 10. c4 {Logical move.} (10. Bd3 {Positional line.} Nh6 $1 11. Qe2 {Normal move.} (11. O-O $2 {Logical move, 70 games, the most played move in the position, but a serious mistake!} Nf7 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 $17 {[%cal Ge6e5] e5 next and Black has a big advantage.}) 11... O-O {For now, Black castles.} (11... Nf7 $6 {is not the same now.} 12. exf6 $36 {[%cal Re2e6,Re7f6] e6 is hanging with check, so Black can't take with the bishop.}) 12. c4 Nf7 $132 {We are ready for this move.}) 10... Nxe5 {My recommendation.} 11. Nxe5 fxe5 12. Bxe5 {The best, and be careful now, to not confuse with 12.cxd5.} Nf6 $1 {The best move, and easy play.}) 6... f6 $5 {[%csl Bf6] This is my recommendation: we avoid the big theory that exists after 6...Nc6, and we just need to study 50 games, not 1000!} 7. O-O {The most played move.} (7. exf6 {Natural move, but not the best.} Nxf6 8. O-O O-O 9. c4 {Logical, and now we have} e5 $1 $146 {Very nice novelty, we can play for an advantage.} 10. Nxe5 Nc6 11. Nxc6 (11. Nf3 $2 Ng4 $17 {[%csl Rf2]}) 11... bxc6 $44 {[%cal Gf6g4] very good compensation because we have Ng4 ideas.}) 7... Nc6 8. Qe2 $1 {Critical continuation.} (8. Bf4 {Logical move, but Black has a strong reply:} g5 $1 {Important move.} 9. Be3 $1 {Only move.} (9. Bg3 $2 {natural, but bad.} f5 $1 {And now it's dangerous only for White.}) 9... Bxe3 10. fxe3 f5 $1 $11 {No problem for Black.}) 8... fxe5 {I like the forced approach.} 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Qxe5 Nf6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc5d6] Our idea is to continue with 00 and Bd6.} *

