{[%evp 0,46,14,21,61,45,45,36,36,41,50,42,51,33,80,25,29,25,47,26,42,25,11,27,27,12,12,6,5,5,48,25,28,-13,-23,-17,-22,-27,-28,-45,-33,-43,-8,2,-16,-40,6,-32,0]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qf4 {The topic of this chapter.} f6 $5 {This is what I prepared some months ago, in the Russian Final against GM Grischuk, it is a very interesting move, my opponent was very surprised, in the end I won that game, but I was not sure if it is a good move for one game, or for long distance. After analyzing this together, we concluded that this is a very serious move and playable for a long time. It is very difficult for White to fight for even the smallest advantage. Good news, that there are also only 10 games here.} (6... e6 {The standard move, and has 400 games, the position is not so forced, and White has a lot of interesting moves.} 7. Nc3 $5 {Basso: I played this one year ago at the Italian Team Championship, against somebody who is playing exclusively Caro-Kann with 3... c5.} (7. Be3 $5 {was how GM Grebnev played against me, also interesting.}) (7. Bd3 {The main move.}) 7... Nb4 {is how Black should continue and after} 8. Qd2 a6 {But it is very strange way to play.}) 7. Nc3 {This is probably White's most critical move.} (7. Bb5 {Grischuk didn't spend too much time, and played the most logical move.} g5 $1 {looks like a very good move, but very bad positional move also! The idea is to play against White's queen.} 8. Qa4 {Grischuk's choice.} (8. Qd2 {Equal move in strength as 8.Qa4, we can check the game Lagarde-Krstulovic, Arad 2024.} a6 {Good move.} 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. c4 $2 {GM Lagarde was surprised, and this is a mistake already.} (10. h3 $146 {is the best for the engine.} Bg7 $132 {New playable position.}) 10... g4 $1 11. Nd4 Qc7 $1 {Strong preparation from Black.} 12. Ne2 {The evaluation is already close to -1.} fxe5 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Qxd5 Bb7 {And White had to go to e6, but after} 15. Qb3 $2 {That was played in the game, Black's position is winning:} Nf6 16. Bg5 {Black played 16...Rb8, but after the improvement} Bxg2 $19 {The evaluation is already -3. So it shows, how difficult it is for White to play this position, if a surprised GM 2600 got a lost position after a few moves. This line has a lot of potential.}) (8. Qg3 {If the queen goes to g3,} Nh6 $1 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gh6f5] Nf5 is our idea, and the queen is short on squares.} 9. O-O {is met with} Nf5 10. Qg4 h5 11. Qa4 g4 {looks very good, but it's not all.} 12. Ng5 $1 {Only good move.} fxg5 13. Bxc6+ {[%cal Rb7c6,Ra4c6,Rc8d7,Rc6g6] And the idea is that now White has the g6 square available.} Bd7 {is enough for equality.} 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7 15. Qxd7+ Kxd7 16. Bxg5 {Black is pawn down for now, but very big compensation.} Rg8 17. Bf4 Nd4 $11 {[%cal Rd4e2,Rd4c2] 2 big threats, equal endgame.}) 8... g4 {The best move.} 9. Nd4 {was played in the game.} (9. Bxc6+ $146 {This is a serious move, and during the game I was a bit scared that I forgot what to do against it.} bxc6 10. Nd4 fxe5 11. Qxc6+ {How to play with Black?} Qd7 $1 {The best move and my analysis, which I remembered during Grischuk's think.} (11... Bd7 $4 {Don't play this move, because after} 12. Qxd5 $18 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gd5h5,Re5d4] Black cannot capture on d4.}) 12. Qxa8 exd4 {And Black plays for compensation, for example:} 13. O-O Bg7 14. Qb8 {The best try, to get the queen back into the game.} Nf6 15. Qb4 O-O {[%cal Ge7e5] Black needs one more move to support the center.} 16. Qxd4 {Forced, but now Black has compensation after any move.} Ne4 17. Qd3 Qc6 {[%cal Gc8a6] And thanks to piece activity and development, Black has full compensation.} 18. Nd2 Ba6 19. c4 Nc5 20. Qg3 Qg6 $36 {[%csl Rc1,Rd2,Rf1][%cal Gc5d3] It looks like a very dangerous position for White, I prefer Black here.}) 9... fxe5 10. Nxc6 {White's most logical move.} (10. Bxc6+ $146 {is transposing to 9.Bxc6, but here it also allows the} Kf7 $5 $13 {Extra option, so White should start with 9.Bxc6 if they want to reach that position.}) 10... bxc6 11. Bxc6+ Bd7 {White has two options:} 12. Nc3 {was played by Grischuk.} (12. c4 {was tried by GM Kollars against Bodrogi, at the EU-Ch 2024.} d4 {Good move.} 13. O-O Nf6 14. Re1 {Black played 14...Rc8, but I like} Bg7 $5 $146 {Just to play for initiative.} 15. Bg5 {It's hard to say what is the best, White is playing positionally, but the position is not better for example:} (15. Rxe5 O-O {There is no need to calculate pawns.} 16. Bxd7 Nxd7 {And White should most likely enter the endgame:} 17. Rd5 Nb6 18. Rxd8 Nxa4 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Nd2 {Pawn up, but positional compensation after} d3 21. Rb1 Rc8 $11 {[%csl Rb1,Rc1,Rd2][%cal Rb2b3,Ga4c3] White's pieces are paralyzed.}) 15... O-O 16. Nd2 Bxc6 17. Qxc6 Qd6 {If White takes, the position is fantastic for Black.} 18. Qa4 a5 {[%cal Rg5f6,Ge7f6] And White cannot play for blockade, cause Bxf6 is met with exf6 of course.} 19. Rac1 Qd7 $13 {And the position is equal and complicated.}) 12... Nf6 13. Bg5 Rc8 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {I offered a draw here, because I couldn't remember what to do after Qxd7.} 15. Qb3 {Grischuk declined and kept queens on the board.} (15. Qxd7+ $146 {If White takes, both options are good:} Nxd7 {is one option, and it is safe.} (15... Kxd7 {is another option, more risky, but also more ambitious.} 16. O-O-O {The best.} (16. Bxf6 {I was afraid of this followed by taking the d5 pawn, but Grischuk's understanding was better.} exf6 17. Nxd5 $6 {is not good.} Rxc2 18. Nxf6+ Ke6 19. Nxg4 Bb4+ {I thought that I have compensation, but in reality after} 20. Kf1 Rf8 $19 {[%csl Rf1] Black's position is just winning.}) 16... d4 17. Rhe1 {Position is complicated, Black has to play} Rg8 $1 18. Bh4 Rc5 {To defend c5.} 19. Bg3 Rg5 $11 {Otherwise, Black's position could be worse, but now it is equal.}) 16. Nxd5 Rxc2 17. b3 (17. O-O {White can sacrifice a pawn, but it is also equal.} Rxb2 $11) 17... e6 18. Ne3 Bb4+ 19. Kf1 Rb2 $11 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Ge3d1,Rb2c2,Gd1e3,Rc2b2] White can't play with the king on f1, so the best is to repeat moves with Nd1-Ne3.}) 15... d4 16. Bxf6 exf6 17. Ne4 Be7 18. O-O f5 {But after some logical moves, he commited a big mistake:} 19. Nd2 $2 {looks natural, but actually the knight does nothing on d2.} (19. Ng3 $1 $146 {was the only good move.} h5 {And the position is very complicated, but 0.00 evaluation.} 20. Rae1 {And White gets some counterplay against the pawns.} e4 (20... h4 {Maybe White was scared of this move, but of course White should play now} 21. Rxe5 $1 {To get counterplay on the e-file.} hxg3 22. Rfe1 $1 {[%cal Ge5e7] White will take on e7, and it will be an equal position.} gxh2+ 23. Kh1 Kf8 24. Rxe7 Qxe7 25. Rxe7 Kxe7 $11 {White is fighting maximum for a draw.}) 21. Ne2 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Re2d4]} Bc5 $13 {[%cal Ge1d1] Equal position according to engine, playable for both sides.}) 19... e4 $1 $19 {The evaluation is -2 for Black.} 20. Rad1 {I didn't find the best move:} Qc6 $2 {I played this natural move, but it allows counterplay.} (20... Kf8 $19 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gf8g7] When I showed this position to GM Kramnik, at recent Olympiad, he found this move in 10 seconds. King safety is very important! Evaluation is more than -2.}) (20... Bf6 $5 $19 {is also a good move.}) 21. Rfe1 {White didn't find it.} (21. Nxe4 $3 {Brilliant sacrifice, and White has a normal position.} fxe4 22. Rxd4 $44 {[%csl Re8] The king is in the center, compensation is full.}) 21... Rf8 {And before sacrificing on e4, White first needs to include h3-h5., but it is very difficult to understand it.} 22. Nf1 $6 (22. h3 $1 $13) 22... Qxc2 23. Qb5+ Qc6 $15 {I was only slightly better in the endgame, but we can stop here.}) (7. Qg3 {If White starts with this move,} g5 {And White's best is anyway} 8. Bb5 {That transposes to 7.Bb5.}) 7... a6 $1 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Rf1b5] Important move to stop Bb5.} (7... e6 $2 {would be a serious mistake.} 8. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Ge5f6,Gb5c7] And Black's position is critical.} g5 {doesn't help now.} (8... a6 $2 9. exf6 $16 {[%cal Gf6f7]}) 9. Qg3 a6 10. Nbd4 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 $16 {And it's just a bad position for Black.}) (7... g5 $2 {also not good.} 8. Qa4 Bd7 9. exf6 g4 {looks more or less interesting, but White has} 10. f7+ $1 {Intermezzo.} Kxf7 11. Ng5+ Kg7 12. Nxd5 e5 13. c3 $14 {[%cal Gc6d4] And the line continues, but it's advantage for the engine.}) 8. Qg3 $5 $146 {is a move suggested by the engine.} (8. Be3 {was played by GM Hong.} e6 {[%cal Gd8c7] Black's idea is Qc7, with just good position.} 9. O-O-O {The only move we need to analyze.} fxe5 {We are not scared of this structure.} 10. Nxe5 Nf6 {Black just has a playable position:} 11. Qa4 {was played in the game.} Qc7 12. f4 Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5] The best move, Black needs to provide b5.} 13. Qb3 $146 {White can continue, but looks also risky.} (13. Ba7 Ra8 14. Be3 Rb8 $11 {Draw by repetition.}) 13... Nxe5 {Not the only option, so don't be scared of preparation, Black has many other options.} 14. fxe5 Nd7 {We can win a pawn.} 15. Ne2 Nxe5 16. Nf4 Bd6 17. Bb6 Qc6 $11 {Very rich position, we can't analyze until endgame, but Black is normal here.}) (8. exf6 {don't be afraid of this structure.} Nxf6 9. Bd3 e6 $11 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gf8d6] The position is just normal, and French players know that this structure is okay for Black, also the queen on f4 is not fantastic here.}) (8. Bd2 $6 {was played in Fernandez-Mareco, but it is just a bad version of Be3.} e6 9. O-O-O fxe5 10. Nxe5 Nf6 $36 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8] The bishop is misplaced on d2, not a serious line.}) (8. Bd3 $146 {is the most serious and the most logical move.} fxe5 $1 9. Nxe5 Nf6 {Standard reaction, the best.} 10. O-O {Logical move.} (10. Nf3 {[%cal Ge7e6,Yg7g6] is a possible move, you have a lot of good options, like e6 or g6, or another draw by repetition:} Bg4 11. Ne5 Bc8 $11 {One more draw by repetition.}) 10... e6 {with Bd6 idea.} 11. Nxc6 {White must take.} bxc6 {We are ready for Bd6 with tempo, so White should retreat the queen somewhere.} 12. Qg3 {[%cal Rg3g7] To stop the development, but Black has a nice move:} (12. Qg5 {is also met with} Ra7 $1 $11 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Ga7g7,Gf8d6] With natural development, and very easy to play position.}) 12... Ra7 $1 $11 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Ga7g7,Gf8d6] To protect g7, with Bd6 tempo next.}) 8... fxe5 $1 {[%cal Rc1f4] We must take on e5 before White is able to reinforce the e5 knight with the bishop.} (8... e6 $6 {Don't play e6 now, because White's idea is} 9. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf3e5,Gf4e5] To support the e5 pawn, and we don't have the typical capture on e5 idea.} g5 10. Be3 $16 {Just bad position.}) (8... d4 $6 {wins a pawn, but White is slightly better in the endgame after} 9. Ne4 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qxe5 12. Qxe5 fxe5 13. Ng5 $14 {[%cal Gf1c4] White has more than compensation in the endgame.}) 9. Nxe5 Nf6 {[%cal Rc1f4,Gf6h5] Good move, since Bf4 is met with Nh5.} (9... Nxe5 {If we take on e5 now, White has a fantastic idea in mind:} 10. Qxe5 e6 11. Be2 Nf6 {looks normal, next move Bd6, but} 12. Bh5+ $1 {Very strong move.} g6 13. Nxd5 $1 {White's idea.} Nxd5 14. Qxh8 gxh5 15. Qxh7 $14 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gh7h5,Gc7f7,Gh5f7] And position is still unclear, after Qc7-Qh5-Qxf7, but White must be a bit better in the endgame, thanks to the pawns on the kingside. I am a bit afraid to play it.}) 10. Be2 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Ge2h5] White stops Nh5.} (10. Bf4 $6 {We are not scared of it now.} Nh5 $1 $15 {[%cal Gh5f4] With better position.}) (10. Bd3 {Now be careful.} Nxe5 $1 {Important to take before White can play Bf4-Bxe5.} (10... e6 $6 {No time for it.} 11. Bf4 $1 {And the point is that} Nh5 $4 {is met with} 12. Bg6+ $1 $18 {And White is just winning.}) 11. Qxe5 e6 {[%cal Gf8d6] We are ready for Bd6 or Bc5 (if White plays Bf4).} 12. Qg3 {[%csl Rg7] White targets the pawn, and we don't have the nice Ra7 anymore, but} Qd7 $11 {To defend it, next Bd6 with normal position.}) 10... Bf5 {[%csl Gf5] But here we can develop the bishop to a nice square.} 11. Bf4 (11. O-O Nxe5 12. Qxe5 e6 13. Bf4 Qd7 $11 {Good playable position.}) 11... e6 12. O-O (12. O-O-O Rc8 $132 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gc8c1] Counterplay on the c-file.}) 12... g6 {[%csl Gg1,Gg6][%cal Rh2h4,Gf8g7] When White's king is on g1, we can play g6, because no h4 ideas, and Black is okay.} 13. Nxc6 {Sample line:} bxc6 14. Bc7 Qd7 15. Be5 Bg7 16. Qe3 O-O 17. h3 h5 $11 {Absolutely normal position. Evaluation is +0.15, but it will probably be less, if you wait for 2 minutes.} *

