{[%evp 0,46,14,20,57,57,57,41,41,36,42,27,36,0,16,17,17,17,17,2,18,12,23,1,1,8,-7,-7,-7,6,19,0,0,25,5,8,41,0,-10,22,22,22,19,0,0,0,0,0,6]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {In the previous chapter, we analyzed the mainline 6.Nxc6, but White also has other options.} 6. c4 {Important line.} (6. f4 {not a serious move, but let's check the game Alekseenko-Iljushenok, 2019.} Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6f5] typical good move when White plays f2-f4.} 7. c3 Nf5 $1 8. Nf3 f6 $5 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] my recommendation. We don't play e6 because probably we will play g6-Bg7.} (8... e6 {also possible, but after} 9. Bd3 Bc5 10. Qe2 $132 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f1,Yc1d2,Ye1c1] White can play Nbd2-Nf1-Bd2- 0-0-0. It's an equal but playable position.}) 9. Bd3 g6 $11 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] Bg7- 0-0 next. We can decide if we want to include fxe5-fxe5, according to the situation.}) (6. Bb5 {Rare line, but White has some tricky ideas here.} Bd7 7. Nxc6 Bxc6 $1 ({but not} 7... bxc6 $6 8. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Rd7] because White is playing the 6.Nc6 line, where our bishop is misplaced on d7 (no a5-Ba6 plan).}) 8. Bd3 {only 8 games, but this is an important position.} (8. Bxc6+ {doesn't make sense.} bxc6 9. O-O e6 $11 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7g6,Bf8e7,Be8g8] we are playing the 6.Nxc6 line, where we don't even need to spend time for a5-Ba6 to exchange the bishops.}) 8... d4 $1 {[%csl Bd4] important move.} ({if we just play the normal} 8... e6 9. Nd2 Ne7 10. Qg4 Ng6 11. Nf3 Qc7 12. Qg3 $14 {White achieves a slightly better and playable position.}) 9. Nd2 $5 {most tricky line. It was only played once by GM Horvath Dominik.} ({The key point is that after} 9. O-O $6 {we have} Qd5 $1 $15 {[%cal Gd5e5] Qxe5 next.}) (9. Qe2 e6 {against Qe2 we can also just play e6.} (9... Bxg2 {also possible, but very complicated.} 10. f3 Bh3 11. Nd2 a6 $13 {the position is very unclear, and the engine's evaluation is "0.00".}) 10. O-O Qd5 11. f3 (11. f4 Nh6 $11) 11... Bc5 $11 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8] Ne7 - 0-0 next. No problems.}) 9... Bxg2 $1 {we must take the pawn.} ({Now we shouldn't play normally because after} 9... e6 10. O-O Qd5 {White has} 11. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e4,Ga2a3,Gb2b4] and this is the difference between 8.Qe2 and 8.Nd2.}) 10. f3 $5 {Horvath was very well-prepared.} (10. Rg1 {most natural continuation.} Bc6 11. Nb3 e6 12. Qe2 g6 $5 {[%cal Gf8h6] Bh6 next and Black is fine, for example:} 13. Bd2 Bh6 14. O-O-O Bxd2+ 15. Rxd2 Ne7 $132 {[%cal Gd8c7,Ge8c8,Ce8g8] We can play short castle, or maybe Qc7 and long castle.} 16. Rg4 Qc7 17. Nxd4 O-O-O) 10... Qa5 $5 $146 {[%cal Rd3b5,Ga5e5] this is my recommendation. I want to stop Bb5 with the active Qa5 move.} (10... a6 {useful move, but not our priority.} 11. Rg1 Bh3 12. Nb3 g6 13. Be4 Qb6 14. Qxd4 $14 {Horvath-Aczel, 2024.}) 11. Rg1 Bh3 12. f4 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gd3e4] best move, with the idea Qf3-Be4.} O-O-O 13. Qf3 Be6 $1 {[%cal Ge6d5] we are ready to play Bd5.} 14. Be4 Bd5 {most concrete continuation.} (14... Qc7 $5 15. f5 Bd7 16. Nb3 e6 $13 {is another possible direction.} 17. Nxd4 Bc5 18. fxe6 Bxd4 19. exd7+ Rxd7) 15. b4 $1 Qb5 16. Bb2 (16. a4 Qd7 $15) 16... Bxe4 17. Qxe4 e6 18. a3 Nh6 $132 {[%cal Gh6f5] Nf5 next and it looks very easy-to-play for us.}) (6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3) 6... dxc4 $5 {Practical solution and our main recommendation. Here, you just need to remember one important line, and not a lot of forced variations like in the 6.. .e6 line.} (6... e6 {is Black's most common continuation, and it's also a good line, but here you will need to remember a lot.} 7. Nc3 Bc5 {[%csl Gc5] our recommendation.} (7... Bb4 {also possible, but we prefer 7...Bc5.}) 8. Nxc6 (8. Nb3 {very rare, but it was played by Artemiev against Dreev.} Bb4 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bb5 Nge7 11. O-O O-O $11 {Black is doing fine.} 12. Qe2 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ye2e5] Artemiev defends e5 and is ready to play Rd1-Bg5...} Be6 {[%csl Ge6] this is probably Black's most useful move in the position.} (12... a6 {was played by Alexey, but maybe it's not so neccessary because White's bishop will be better placed on d3.} 13. Bd3 d4 14. Na4 $36 {[%cal Ga4c5] Nac5 sometimes, and it became more pleasant for White in Artemiev-Dreev, 2024.}) 13. Bg5 {most logical move.} (13. Bd3 $6 {White can play like in the game Artemiev-Dreev, but now it's different:} d4 $1 14. Na4 $2 {not good because of} Bxb3 15. axb3 Qd5 $17) (13. Rd1 a6 14. Bd3 d4 15. Na4 Bxb3 16. axb3 b5 $15) 13... h6 14. Bh4 d4 $5 {engine's solution.} (14... Qc7 {also possible, for example:} 15. Bxc6 Nxc6 16. f4 Qb6+ 17. Kh1 Be7 $132 {equal and playable.}) 15. Rfd1 (15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Rfd1 Bxb3 17. axb3 Qd7 $11) 15... Qc7 {White wins a pawn after} 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Rxd4 Rfd8 $44 {[%csl Bb4,Be6] But we have full compensation thanks to the strong two bishops.}) 8... bxc6 {Now, White has two serious lines: the concrete 9.Qg4 and the positional 9.cxd5.} 9. Qg4 {most concrete continuation.} (9. Qa4 $6 Ne7 $15 {[%csl Ra4] Qa4 is misplaced.}) (9. Bd3 $6 {allows} dxc4 $1 10. Bxc4 Qxd1+ 11. Nxd1 Ne7 $15 {[%csl Oe5][%cal Gc5d4,Ge7g6,Ga8b8] slightly better for Black because of the more active pieces, and also e5 is very often a problem for White.}) (9. cxd5 {now both cxd5 and exd5 are good.} cxd5 {also possible, but you will need to remember some lines.} (9... exd5 10. Bd3 Ne7 {[%cal Gc8f5,Ge8g8] Black's plan is just Bf5 and 0-0.} 11. O-O Bf5 {White can go for some small tries, but it will be equal in the end.} 12. Na4 Bb6 13. Bg5 Qd7 $1 (13... Bxd3 $6 14. Qxd3 h6 15. Be3 $14 {Kulaots-Tisdall, 2024.}) 14. Bxe7 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Qxe7 16. Rac1 O-O 17. Rxc6 Qxe5 $11 {just equal.}) 10. b4 $1 {[%csl Gb4] critical.} (10. Qg4 Ne7 11. Qxg7 Rg8 12. Qxh7 Bd7 $132 {better version for Black compared to 9.Qg4, because cxd5-cxd5 is a good inclusion for Black.}) 10... Be7 11. a3 (11. Bd2 $5 Nh6 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf7f6] 00-f6 next. Things will not be 100% trivial, but objectively Black is doing fine.}) 11... a5 $1 12. bxa5 Qxa5 13. Bd2 {[%cal Gc3b5]} Bg5 $1 {key move, and after some concrete lines Black equalizes, for example:} 14. Bb5+ Bd7 15. Rb1 $1 Ne7 16. f4 Bxf4 17. Bxd7+ Kxd7 18. Rb7+ Kd8 19. Nb5 Bxd2+ 20. Qxd2 Ng6 21. Qxa5+ Rxa5 22. O-O Nxe5 23. Rb8+ Ke7 24. Rxh8 Rxb5 $11) 9... Ne7 $1 {we ofcourse don't play g6/kf8.} 10. Qxg7 Ng6 (10... Rg8 {I don't like this direction.} 11. Qxh7 Rb8 12. Qc2 Nf5 {For the engine, this position is more or less fine, but for a human, it could be very difficult to handle—for example:} 13. g3 Qa5 14. a3 Nd4 $1 15. Qh7 Nf3+ 16. Kd1 Rf8 17. Rb1 dxc4 18. Bg2 Nxe5 19. Ke2 {This is just one example variation, but in general, White has many possible moves, making it very difficult to determine where to stop the analysis. If you try to play this over the board without prior preparation, one single mistake could be enough to end up in a seriously worse position.}) 11. Be2 Bf8 {most logical and common continuation, but things are not so clear after} (11... h5 $5 {Engine’s idea. Compared to the previous line with 11...Bf8, the key point is that when Black eventually captures on e5 with the knight, White won’t have the option to play Qh5.} 12. O-O Bf8 (12... Bd4 $5 {possible, and if you check with the engine it will show equality, but Black needs to find a lot of difficult moves:} 13. Bf4 Bc5 $1 {only move :)} 14. Be3 d4 15. Ne4 Bf8 16. Nf6+ Ke7 17. Ng8+ Ke8 {White can make a draw, but also play on with} 18. Qxh8 $5 Nxh8 19. Nf6+ Ke7 20. Bg5 Qa5 $1 21. c5 $1 {[%eval 0,0] in many ways, but maybe we will need to find some other difficult moves at some point...}) 13. Qf6 Be7 14. Qf3 Nxe5 15. Qe3 $36 {but this is also very risky-to play.}) 12. Qf6 Be7 13. Qf3 h5 {probably the best.} (13... Nxe5 14. Qh5 $1 $14 {[%csl Gh5]}) (13... d4 {mainline, but very risky:} 14. Ne4 Qa5+ 15. Bd2 (15. Kf1 $5 {also interesting.} Qxe5 16. Nf6+ Kd8 17. Ng4 $36) 15... Qxe5 16. h4 $1 f5 17. Ng5 Rb8 18. h5 Nf8 19. O-O Bd6 20. Qxc6+ Bd7 21. f4 Bxc6 22. fxe5 $14 {I don't think that Black immediately equalizes here.}) 14. O-O Nxe5 $13 {No games have been played here. For the engine, this is equal, but OTB, I’m not sure it’s so easy to play. White can try 15.Qe3, 15.Qg3, or 15.Qh3, and there is no clear end to the lines. However, if you enjoy uncertainty and a complex position, then this is definitely a playable option!}) 7. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 bxc6 9. Bxc4 Bf5 $1 {[%csl Cc6][%cal Bg8e7,Be7d5,Ge7e6] At first glance, this endgame might seem slightly unpleasant due to the c6 and a7 pawns. However, in reality, it is completely equal. Our pawn on c6 is actually useful, as it helps us execute the key maneuver Ne7-Nd5.} 10. Be3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Ga1c1] This is the critical line. White's idea is Nd2-Rc1.} (10. Ke2 e6 11. Rd1 {engine's idea is Bd3.} Ne7 12. Bd3 Rd8 (12... Bxd3+ 13. Rxd3 Nd5 14. Na3 $14 {/=. could be slightly more pleasant for White, but it's also very close to equal.}) 13. Bxf5 Rxd1 14. Kxd1 Nxf5 $11 {just no problem, for example:} 15. Nd2 Bc5 16. Ke2 h5 {[%csl Cf5,Gh5] useful move to support our Nf5.} 17. Nc4 Ke7 $11) (10. Nc3 {White's most common continuation.} e6 11. Be3 (11. Ke2 Ne7 12. Rd1 Nd5 $11 {[%cal Gf8e7] Be7 next and no problem.}) 11... Ne7 (11... g6 $5 $146 {[%cal Gf8g7] also interesting: Bg7 next, and we can always secure our Bf5 with the move h7-h5.}) 12. Ke2 (12. Rc1 g5 $5 {[%csl Yg5] useful-to-know idea.} 13. Ke2 (13. Bxg5 Rg8 14. Bxe7 {if White retreats the bishop, we just play Rxg2.} Kxe7 15. g3 Bg7 16. f4 f6 17. exf6+ Bxf6 $44 {[%csl Bf5,Bf6] full compensation thanks to the two strong bishops.}) 13... Bg7 14. Bxg5 Bxe5 15. g3 Nd5 $44 {good playable endgame.}) 12... Nd5 (12... g5 $5 {also possible to play it here.}) 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Bb3 O-O-O $1 {[%csl Cc6][%cal Gc8b7] our king will defend c6 from b7.} 15. Bxa7 {looks critical, but it's also harmless:} (15. Rac1 Kb7 16. Rhd1 Bb4 $11 {[%cal Gb4a5,Ga5b6] Ba5-Bb6 next.}) 15... Kb7 16. Be3 Re8 {[%csl Re5] White cannot maintain the extra pawn.} 17. Rhd1 (17. f4 $6 g5 $1 18. g3 f6 $1 $15 {[%csl Re2] already worse for White.}) 17... Rxe5 18. Kf1 Bd6 $11) 10... e6 11. Nd2 Ne7 12. Rc1 (12. Bc5 $2 Ng6 $15 {[%csl Re5]}) 12... Nd5 {[%cal Gd5e3] if we take on e3, it will just be equal of course.} 13. Bxd5 cxd5 14. Rc7 {critical position.} ({After} 14. Ke2 Kd7 $11 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gh8c8] Be7-Rhc8, and full equality minimum. In the long-term we can also hope for something more, thanks to our two bishops.}) 14... f6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] important move.} (14... a5 $2 15. Ke2 $16 {[%cal Gh1c1,Gd2b3] Rhc1-Nb3, and White's pieces are too active.}) 15. Bd4 {critical.} (15. exf6 $6 {positional mistake.} gxf6 16. Rxa7 $2 {very easy to play like this for a human, but after} (16. Nb3 Bd6 $15 {positionally better, thanks to the two bishops and to the strong center.}) 16... Rxa7 17. Bxa7 Rg8 $19 {Engine's evaluation is -3,00!}) (15. f4 Kd8 {now f7 is not hanging.} 16. Rxa7 Rxa7 17. Bxa7 fxe5 18. fxe5 Be7 $44 {[%csl Ge7,Gf5][%cal Gd8d7,Gh8a8] Full compensation.}) 15... Kd8 $1 16. Rb7 Kc8 17. Rb3 {or 17.Rb5 will be the same.} Kd7 $1 $146 {[%csl Bd7] very important move to remember.} (17... Rb8 $2 18. Rxb8+ Kxb8 {Cornette-Sandhu, 2005.} 19. Ke2 $1 $16 {[%cal Gh1c1] Rc1 next and White is better.}) 18. exf6 {critical.} (18. Rb7+ $6 Kc6 19. Rb3 fxe5 20. Bxe5 Bd6 $36) (18. Ke2 fxe5 19. Bxe5 Bd6 $11 {equal but I would take Black.}) 18... gxf6 19. Rb7+ (19. Bxf6 Rg8 20. g3 Rc8 $44 {full compensation for sure.}) 19... Kc6 20. Rf7 Bh6 $1 {last detail to fully equalize.} 21. Bxf6 (21. Rxf6 Bg7 22. Rxf5 Bxd4 $44 {[%csl Cd4] with the strong Bd4, it's obvious full compensation.}) 21... Rhf8 22. Rxf8 Rxf8 23. Bd4 a5 $44 {[%cal Gc6d6,Gf8c8] Two strong bishops and also here it's full compensation. We can conclude that after 6.c4, Black has two main options: - 6. ..e6, which is a strong and solid variation, but requires remembering many details. - 6...dxc4, a more practical choice where Black only needs to remember one key line, making it much easier to handle over the board with minimal memorization effort.} *

