{[%evp 0,36,14,20,57,57,57,36,36,32,32,32,53,37,18,3,-9,6,53,14,44,21,29,-6,58,73,80,6,-6,-4,-15,-9,-17,-11,-10,-10,-8,-7,20]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 e6 5. Be3 {The most concrete move, White wants to keep the extra pawn.} Nd7 6. Bb5 {Critical and most interesting.} (6. Nf3 {Positional line, but harmless.} Bxc5 7. Bxc5 Nxc5 {We have a French structure, but White's pawn is on f2 and not on f4, which makes this position safer for Black, an improved version.} 8. Qd4 {Most common move, White develops with tempo.} (8. Nbd2 {Normal development, but poses no problems.} Ne7 9. Nb3 Bd7 {The knight is defended tactically.} (9... Nxb3 {No need to take on b3, because it opens up the rook.} 10. axb3 $132 {[%csl Ga1][%cal Gb3b4] White's rook is active now, and White's doubled pawns are fine.}) 10. Nxc5 Qa5+ $1 {The point.} 11. c3 Qxc5 12. Bd3 {Black can change bishops with} Bb5 $11 {Absolutely fine position.}) 8... Qb6 $1 {The best.} (8... Ne4 $2 {is bad.} 9. Nbd2 {Comparing to 8.Nbd2, White has extra tempi:} Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Ne7 11. Bd3 Bd7 12. O-O Qb6 13. a4 $14 {[%cal Rd7b5] No Bb5, and White's position is slightly better.}) 9. Nbd2 (9. a4 {White's idea is a5.} a5 {[%cal Ra4a5] Better to stop it, now White has no ideas.} (9... Ne7 10. a5 Qc7 11. Na3 $36 {[%cal Gb2b4] White is playing for expansion, which is at least something.}) 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Na3 Ne7 {White will get the b5 square, but it's more important for Black that the bishops are traded.} 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. Nb5 O-O 14. O-O Qxd4 15. Nbxd4 Nc6 $36 {If anyone can be better, it's Black.}) (9. Nc3 {White develops the knight, to have also Na4 ideas in future.} Ne7 10. O-O-O O-O {[%cal Ge7c6] Next move is Nc6.} 11. Bd3 {Logical square for the bishop, but the thing is that Black can always take on d3, which means no attack:} f6 {Better to start from this.} 12. Na4 Nxd3+ 13. Qxd3 Qc7 $132 {Playable position for Black, counterplay in the center.}) 9... Ne7 10. Nb3 {You can take on b3, or more interesting is} Ne4 $5 {We are not afraid of doubled pawns.} 11. Qxb6 axb6 {[%csl Ga8,Gb6] No way to attack the pawns, and the a-file is semi-open for the rook now.} 12. a3 {White will need to lose tempo with this.} Bd7 13. Bd3 f6 $132 {Good French endgame for Black.}) 6... Ne7 {No panic, we finish development.} 7. Bd4 $1 {Best move, according to the engine.} (7. Nf3 {Most common way.} Nf5 {Good move to attack the e3 bishop.} 8. b4 {Necessary move.} (8. Bd4 $6 {is dubious.} Qa5+ $1 9. Nc3 a6 $15 {[%csl Rc5] Black will regain c5, with a better position.}) 8... a6 $5 {I think the inclusion is useful for Black.} (8... Nxe3 {is also possible, just to play for compensation.} 9. fxe3 a5 10. c3 Be7 {Better to develop the bishop on e7 now.} 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 Qc7 13. Qd4 f6 14. Bxd7 Bxd7 $11 {Also good position for Black, full compensation.}) 9. Ba4 a5 {This is Black's counterplay idea.} (9... Nxe3 {You can start with this move as well.} 10. fxe3 a5 {leads to the same.}) 10. c3 Nxe3 11. fxe3 g6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8g7] We want to develop the bishop on the long diagonal, to put pressure on e5 and later c3.} 12. O-O Bg7 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Rd1d4,Ga5b4] Comparing to a position where we didn't include a6-Ba4, now it's risky for White to go for Qd4, since after axb4 the a4 bishop is potentially hanging.} 13. c6 {Most logical.} bxc6 14. Bxc6 Rb8 15. b5 O-O {We are ready to take on e5.} 16. Bxd7 Bxd7 17. a4 {Qc7 is possible, but the best is} f6 $1 {[%csl Gg7] To immediately open the bishop.} 18. exf6 Qxf6 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc3] White has development problems.} 19. Ra2 Qe7 $132 {[%csl Rc3,Gd5,Re3,Ge6] Full compensation, Black has 2 bishops, center, and weak pawns to target.}) (7. b4 Nf5 8. Nf3 {transposes to 7.Nf3.}) (7. c3 $5 {Tricky move.} a6 $1 {[%csl Ga6] Here, it is important to include this move.} (7... Nc6 $6 {Logical, but not the most accurate.} 8. b4 $1 {White defends the important c5 pawn.} Ndxe5 9. f4 $14 {[%csl Gb5] And it could be slight advantage for White.}) 8. Ba4 {When the bishop leaves the b5 square, now our knight can jump to c4 after} (8. Bxd7+ {is a different story, Black is always happy with pair of bishops.} Bxd7 9. Nf3 Nf5 10. Bd4 {And a good reaction is} Nxd4 $1 11. cxd4 b6 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rb2b4,Ga6a5] White cannot keep the pawn chain locked.} 12. cxb6 Qxb6 {Black has full compensation, and maybe is even better.} 13. Qb3 {Only move, to hold b2.} Rb8 14. Qxb6 Rxb6 15. b3 Rc6 $36 {White has development issues, could be slightly better for Black.}) 8... Nc6 9. b4 Ndxe5 $36 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ge5c4,Rf2f4] The bishop left b5, so f4 is not scary for Black.}) 7... Nf5 {Very solid choice, and also simpler to play, in my opinion.} (7... Nc6 $5 {is a good way for a complex battle.} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. b4 a5 {Undermine the pawn structure.} 10. a3 Ba6 {To stop White from castling.} 11. f4 {The best for the engine, but after} (11. Ne2 $6 {is logical, to play castle, but too slow.} Qb8 $1 $15 {[%csl Rb4,Re5] Double attack, Black is better.}) 11... g5 $1 $13 {Good move to destroy the pawn chain. Position is very complicated, and the cost of one move is high for both players. It is up to you, you can keep this option, if you need to play for a win at all cost.}) 8. c3 {The most logical.} (8. Nf3 $6 {harmless move.} Qa5+ $1 9. Nc3 a6 $15 {[%csl Rc5] c5 pawn drops.}) 8... Be7 {Finish development.} (8... a6 $6 {No need to include a6 now, because White has the c2 square for the bishop, for example:} 9. Ba4 Be7 10. Nf3 O-O 11. Bc2 $36 {[%csl Gc2] White has a position with extra tempo, because when we will retake on c5, there will be no tempo, compared to having a bishop on d3.}) 9. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2b3] The best, to defend the pawn with the knight.} (9. Nf3 {No independent value.} O-O 10. b4 a5 {Transposition.}) (9. b4 O-O 10. Nf3 {This can be reached from both move orders.} a5 11. O-O b6 $1 {[%cal Rc5b6,Ga5b4] Immediately go for counterplay.} (11... Qc7 $2 {is a waste of time.} 12. a3 b6 13. Bxd7 Bxd7 14. cxb6 $14 {[%csl Rc7] This looks better for White, also tempo against the queen.}) 12. c6 {The best.} Nb8 $11 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gb8c6] Black will regain the c6 pawn, with good position.}) 9... O-O 10. Nb3 {The most logical.} (10. b4 $2 {is not good now.} a5 11. a3 b6 $1 12. c6 Nb8 $15 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gd8c7] And it is like the 9.b4 line, but White still didn't finish development.}) 10... b6 $1 {Very important moment, we don't need to recapture material, but play this typical move for compensation.} (10... Qc7 $6 {is not accurate.} 11. Nf3 Nxc5 12. Bxc5 $1 {Important capture.} (12. Nxc5 $2 {is bad, because of} Nxd4 $1 {Intermediate move.} 13. cxd4 Qa5+ $1 $15 {[%csl Rb5,Re1] The point.}) 12... Bxc5 13. Nxc5 Qxc5 14. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Gd3,Gf3] This is a good version of the French for White, because our development is not so good, and the knight on f5 is also not good.}) 11. c6 {Logical move.} (11. cxb6 {White had to do something with the pawn.} Nxd4 {Good intermezzo.} 12. Qxd4 {Black can take on b6 or even play the interesting} (12. Nxd4 Qxb6 {Black has just compensation, for example:} 13. Ngf3 f6 $1 {The best, counterplay in the center.} 14. Bxd7 Bxd7 15. Qe2 {Black has a lot of good moves now:} Rab8 (15... Bc8 $5 $11 {[%cal Re1g1,Gc8a6] is also interesting, to stop castle.}) 16. Rb1 Be8 $11 {is one good way for full compensation.}) 12... f6 $5 {For a very complicated game, where White is also risking.} (12... Nxb6 {Just good compensation.} 13. Nf3 Qc7 $44 {[%cal Ga8b8] Very nice French, the pawn is not important here.}) 13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. Nf3 Ba6 $13 {[%csl Re1] Position for 3 results, but White has problems with the king on e1.}) 11... Nc5 12. Nf3 Qc7 {If Black manages to recapture c6, just good position.} 13. g4 $5 {The last critical move for White.} (13. O-O {is nothing.} a6 14. Be2 Qxc6 $11 {Normal position for Black.}) 13... Nxd4 14. cxd4 {And now very important move:} a6 $1 {Nice intermezzo.} (14... f6 $5 {is one alternative, but it's too much, of course. White has a lot of options.} 15. dxc5 fxe5 $13 {is Black's idea.}) 15. Be2 Nxb3 16. Qxb3 Qxc6 {We regain material balance.} 17. O-O Bd7 18. Rfc1 Qa4 $11 {Just equal position.} *

