{[%evp 0,44,14,16,55,53,57,41,41,36,36,19,14,14,36,53,49,37,59,-3,16,-2,11,-40,-35,-48,-58,-12,-11,-17,-13,-8,-9,18,-2,-20,32,11,-17,-17,-18,-18,-18,-36,-23,-33,-37]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 e6 5. Nf3 ({The same position could also arise from the following move order:} 5. a3 Bxc5 6. b4 Be7 7. Nf3 f6 $1 {Transposition.}) 5... Bxc5 6. a3 f6 $1 7. b4 Be7 $1 {Starting postion of the Chapter. The bishop on e7 is flexible, it supports a7-a5 idea, while guarding f6 pawn. The knight from g8 can develop to h6 (when the c1 bishop leaves the diagonal) or to f6 (after fxe5).} 8. Bb2 {mainline.} (8. c4 {Logical and concrete try, but nobody plays this move nowadays.} fxe5 9. Nxe5 {The most logical.} (9. cxd5 $5 {Tricky, because Black has to know the right reaction.} Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gf6] Very important to remember it. Black must finish development.} (9... exd5 $2 {Natural, but mistake.} 10. Bb5+ $1 {[%cal Rc8d7,Gd1d5] And there is no Bd7 move, because of Qxd5.} Nc6 11. Nxe5 $16 {[%cal Ge5c6,Gd1h5] Big advantage for White.}) 10. Bb5+ {Critical line.} (10. Nc3 exd5 {It's possible to take now, because the knight is on f6.} 11. Bb5+ Bd7 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Rd1d5] There is no Qxd5.} 12. Nxe5 Bxb5 13. Nxb5 O-O {[%cal Gb8c6,Ga7a5] The position is equal, for example:} 14. O-O Nc6 {Not afraid to transform the structure.} 15. Nxc6 (15. Bb2 {is playable after a5 or} Qb6 $132 {Easy for Black, position for 3 results.}) 15... bxc6 16. Nd4 Qd7 {c6 pawn is a weakness for now, but no way to exploit it.} 17. Qc2 Rac8 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5] c5 next, with no problem for Black.}) 10... Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. dxe6 {White is playing for the isolated e5 pawn.} Qxe6 {Keeping queens on the board is nice, Black has very easy play.} (12... Qxd1+ {You can also trade queens.} 13. Kxd1 Nc6 {The endgame is equal, for example:} 14. Re1 Rd8+ {[%cal Ge8g8] Stronger, the king will go to short castle, so the h8-rook comes immediately in the game.} 15. Nbd2 e4 16. Ng5 O-O {This endgame is also playable for 3 results.} 17. Kc2 e3 $1 {[%cal Re1e3,Gf6d5] And the situation is risky for White actually:} 18. fxe3 Nd5 19. Ngf3 Rc8 {[%csl Rc2] White has problems with the king.} 20. Kb3 a5 21. Ne4 $1 {The only good move.} (21. b5 $2 {White loses after} a4+ $1 22. Kxa4 Nd4 $3 {[%csl Ra4] or Na5 with same idea, the king is in a mating net.} 23. Nxd4 Rc3 $19 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gf8a8] No defense from mate.}) 21... axb4 22. axb4 Bxb4 $13 {For the engine, it's equal, but all could happen here.}) 13. O-O a5 {The e5 pawn is not a weakness, it's just a pawn.} 14. b5 (14. Bb2 axb4 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8] Castle next, no problem.}) 14... Nbd7 15. Bb2 O-O 16. Nbd2 Bc5 $11 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gf8f2,Ga8e8] Black can start playing on the f-file. Position for 3 results.}) 9... Nf6 {Natural development for Black.} 10. Bb2 a5 {Black's idea, to get counterplay.} 11. b5 {[%csl Ga5,Gb5] Good inclusion for Black.} Nbd7 {We can change the knight on e5.} 12. Nd2 {Logical.} (12. Nxd7 {White spend 3 tempi, but Black only 1, so it doesn't make sense to exchange the knight.} Bxd7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7e8,Ge8h5] Just equal. Typical plan: 0-0, Be8-Bh5.}) 12... O-O 13. Bd3 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 b6 {The bishop will go to b7, on a nice diagonal.} 15. Qe2 (15. O-O Bb7 $11 {The e6 pawn is not a weakness.}) 15... Bb7 (15... a4 $5 $132 {[%csl Ra3] Positional idea to fix the a3 pawn.}) 16. O-O a4 {[%csl Ra3,Ge7][%cal Ra1a3] Useful tempo, to tie the rook to the defense of a3.} 17. Bb2 {White will need this move, most likely.} Qd7 18. Rae1 Bc5 {Black is not scared of losing the e6 pawn.} 19. Qxe6+ Qxe6 20. Rxe6 Rad8 $44 {[%csl Ra3,Rf2] White has potential weaknesses, and it is not easy to play this position from the White side. Full compensation.}) (8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bd3 {[%csl Yd7] Shirov line. White thinks that Bd7 is misplaced, but it's not true.} Nc6 {Black can use the extra tempo.} 10. Bb2 Nh6 {[%cal Ge8g8] 00 next and Black is fine.} 11. O-O (11. c4 {will lead to the same.}) 11... O-O 12. c4 {This is how the game Shirov-Ghasi, 2023 continued.} Nxe5 {The easiest, to exchange the knights as well.} (12... fxe5 {Black took with the pawn in the game, and invited White to take the d7 bishop, but there is no need.} 13. Nxe5 Bf6 $6 14. Nxd7 $14 {And White has a real advantage.}) 13. Nxe5 fxe5 14. Bxe5 Bf6 {Position is normal, for example:} 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Nd2 Nf7 17. Nf3 Rad8 {Playable for both sides.} 18. Qc2 g6 19. cxd5 exd5 20. Rad1 {Black has many options here, even if it is White to move twice, position is okay for Black.} Bg4 21. Be2 d4 $11 {Just equal position.}) (8. Bd3 a5 9. b5 Nd7 10. Bb2 {will be analyzed in the 8.Bb2 move order.}) 8... a5 $1 {Better to start with a5, because anyway it is useful move.} (8... Nd7 $5 {No need to play it.} 9. Nbd2 $1 {could be slightly better for White.} Nh6 (9... a5 {is now not the same.} 10. Bb5 $14 {[%csl Rd7] And the knight is too early on d7.}) 10. exf6 Bxf6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. c4 $14 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Rd7c5] no c5 square for our knight, that's why a5-b5 is a good inclusion for Black.}) 9. b5 {Most played move.} (9. Nbd2 $5 {White sacrifices a pawn, it is playable, but a pawn is a pawn.} axb4 10. axb4 Rxa1 11. Qxa1 Bxb4 12. Qa4+ Nc6 13. Bb5 {This was the game Durarbayili-Tin, 2022, important move for Black now:} Qa5 $1 $11 {And go to ending.} 14. O-O Qxa4 15. Bxa4 Kf7 $11 {White has a compensation for equality, I agree, but also Black can play with extra pawn.}) 9... Nd7 {Nbd7 makes perfect sense now. White has some options:} 10. Nbd2 {Most logical move. White keeps all options open.} (10. c4 {Logical move.} Nxe5 {My recommendation.} (10... fxe5 $5 {For the computer this is also fine, but I don't like it, because Black will need to play without castling.} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Qxd5 Ngf6 13. Qa2 {And important to play} Nb6 $1 $13 {Otherwise, Black's position could be worse. White has many moves and it's not always easy to play for Black.}) 11. Nxe5 fxe5 12. Bxe5 {The best, and be careful now, to not confuse with 12.cxd5.} (12. cxd5 $6 {a bit dubious.} exd5 13. Bxe5 Bf6 {[%cal Re5f6,Gg8f6] Black has good development and also a passed pawn.} 14. Bxf6 (14. Nc3 {Tactically we can't take on e5, because of Qh5+, but} Qe7 $132 {[%csl Re5][%cal Re7e1] To pin the bishop is good.}) 14... Nxf6 $36 {[%cal Ge8g8] Castle next, and easy to play it.}) 12... Nf6 $1 {The best move.} (12... Bf6 $6 {With the pawn exchanged, this is a good move, but now White can play} 13. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Re6][%cal Rf6e5,Gd1h5,Rd8e7] White waits Nh6 and only then takes on f6. And Black has no pin.} (13. Bxf6 Nxf6 $11) 13... Nh6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Bd3 $14 {This is slightly better for White.}) 13. Nc3 {This is how GM Ponkratov played against Gunina in a recent game.} (13. Bd3 $6 {is met with} dxc4 $1 {And Black has a good endgame.} 14. Bxc4 Qxd1+ 15. Kxd1 a4 $1 $15 {[%csl Ra3] To fix a3 pawn.}) (13. cxd5 $6 {harmless.} Qxd5 14. Qxd5 exd5 $15 {[%cal Ge8f7,Ga5a4] Just good position, slightly better for Black.}) (13. Be2 {Normal move.} O-O 14. O-O Nd7 {I think it's more interesting.} (14... Bd7 $5 $146 {also deserves attention, with Be8 idea.} 15. Nc3 Be8 16. cxd5 exd5 17. Bf3 Bf7 $11 {looks a bit passive, but should be equal.}) 15. Bg3 {Probably better than on b2.} (15. Bb2 Nc5 $13 {[%cal Ge7d6,Ga5a4,Gb7b6] Typical moves: b6-Bd6-a4, just good position.}) 15... Nc5 {[%cal Gb7b6] Same plan, we want b6.} 16. Nc3 {White attacks d5, and now engine line:} d4 17. Na4 d3 {Concrete idea.} (17... Nxa4 {additional option.} 18. Qxa4 e5 {To open the bishop.} 19. Bxe5 d3 20. Rfd1 {Only good move.} Bc5 21. Bxd3 Qg5 {[%csl Ra4] Black is playing for an attack, because White's queen is out of the game for now.} 22. Bg3 h5 $13 {[%csl Ra4,Rg1][%cal Gh5h4] Who is better? Unclear position.}) 18. Bf3 Rxf3 $3 {Fantastic idea.} 19. gxf3 b6 {Black has full positional compensation.} 20. Nxc5 Bxc5 21. Ra2 e5 $1 {Important to protect the d3 pawn.} 22. Rd2 Bf5 23. Re1 Bd4 $5 {is one of the many good options.} 24. Bxe5 Qg5+ 25. Kh1 Bh3 26. Bg3 {Only move.} Bc3 27. Rxd3 Bxe1 28. Qxe1 Rf8 29. Qe3 Qh5 $11 {[%csl Rh1] White is 2 pawns up, but the king is in danger, Black has full compensation.}) 13... O-O 14. Be2 Nd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7b6] I like the Nd7-Nb6 plan.} 15. Bg3 Nb6 16. O-O {More logical.} (16. cxd5 {Harmless, as usual.} exd5 17. O-O Be6 $36 {Very good for Black.}) 16... a4 $5 $132 {[%csl Ra3] fix a3, but Black has many other good moves (Bf6, Nxc4 etc).}) (10. Bd3 {Positional line.} Nh6 $1 11. Qe2 {Normal move.} (11. Nbd2 Nf7 {transposes in 10.Nbd2.}) (11. O-O $2 {Logical move, 70 games, the most played move in the position, but a serious mistake!} Nf7 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 $17 {[%cal Ge6e5] e5 next and Black has a big advantage.}) (11. c4 {was played in the game Pichot-Mareco, 2022, Black has a concrete reaction:} fxe5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 dxc4 {And go to endgame.} 14. Bxc4 Qxd1+ 15. Kxd1 Nf7 16. Bg3 Bf6 17. Ra2 e5 $11 {[%cal Ge8e7,Gc8e6] Ke7-Be6 next. Equal endgame.}) 11... O-O {For now, Black castles.} (11... Nf7 $6 {is not the same now.} 12. exf6 $36 {[%cal Re2e6,Re7f6] e6 is hanging with check, so Black can't take with the bishop.}) 12. c4 Nf7 {We are ready for this move.} 13. cxd5 (13. exf6 Bxf6 {Desired recapture, no problem for Black.} 14. O-O Nc5 15. Nc3 Nd6 $36 {Good position for Black.}) 13... Ndxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 {Necessary.} fxe5 {White needs to close the position, otherwise Black is better.} 16. d6 $1 {The best.} (16. Nc3 $2 {was played by Erigaisi, at the EU-Cup 2024, but it is a huge mistake:} exd5 17. Nxd5 Bc5 {The position is open, White's position is seriously worse.} 18. O-O Be6 19. Ne3 {This was how Erigaisi-Andreikin continued, a good move now is} Kh8 $17 {[%csl Ra3,Gc5,Ge6] With very big advantage.}) 16... Bxd6 17. Nd2 {Black has a nice move:} Ra7 $3 $132 {[%csl Ga7,Ra8][%cal Gb7b6,Ga7d7,Re2e4] b6-Rd7 next. Because b6 was not possible, because of Qe4 double attack.}) 10... Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6f7] Nh6-Nf7 is our plan.} 11. Bd3 {The best, because White is well-prepared against fxe5.} (11. Be2 {was played in the game So-Navara.} fxe5 $1 $146 {Very good extra option.} 12. Nxe5 Bf6 $1 {[%csl Gd3,Re2][%cal Rd1h5] Big difference Bd3 or Be2: no Qh5+ now.} 13. f4 Nf5 $132 {Unclear position, but no problem.}) (11. c4 $6 {is dubious.} fxe5 12. Nxe5 Bf6 $1 {And Qh5 is no problem for us.} 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qxh6 Nxe5 $15 {Position is better.}) 11... Nf7 $1 {This is the best.} (11... fxe5 $6 {Don't take now.} 12. Nxe5 Bf6 13. Qh5+ $14 {[%csl Gd3,Gh5] The bishop control g6, so this check is very annoying.}) 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. c4 $1 {Only move.} (14. O-O $4 {huge mistake!} e5 $1 $19 {[%cal Ge5e4] winning position.}) 14... Nc5 $1 {[%csl Ra1,Gf6][%cal Rd1c2] Better to play it immediately, so that Qc2 is not possible.} (14... O-O $6 {don't rush with castle.} 15. O-O Nc5 16. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Gh7] Tempo on h7, and we didn't play Nc5 to take on d3.}) 15. Bc2 b6 {We finish queenside development first.} 16. cxd5 exd5 17. O-O {And now we can delay castle for one more move.} a4 $1 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Rd2b3] Good move, to play for 3 results, Black stops Nb3 and also to fix the a3 pawn.} (17... O-O {allows} 18. Nb3 $1 {With very safe and easy to play position for White.} Bb7 19. Qd4 $11 {Not advantage, but White is not risking anything.}) 18. Re1+ Be6 19. Qb1 {White stops castle for one move.} h6 {[%cal Ge8g8] No problem, just 0-0 next. The game can develop with:} 20. Qb4 O-O 21. Nd4 Nd6 22. N2f3 Bg4 $132 {[%csl Gc5,Gd6] The knights are very good, and no piece can attack our pawn on d5. Position is for 3 results.} *

