{[%evp 0,40,14,28,57,57,57,36,36,53,53,11,11,7,28,15,18,23,35,24,24,20,10,2,-15,-15,23,7,-6,-15,-12,-26,-15,-7,18,26,24,61,51,55,19,22,37]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 e6 5. Nf3 Bxc5 6. Bd3 {This is an important variation and the topic of this chapter.} f6 $5 {[%csl Bf6] This is my recommendation: we avoid the big theory that exists after 6...Nc6, and we just need to study 50 games, not 1000!} ({After} 6... Nc6 {there is a very big theory: more than 1000 games!}) 7. O-O {The most played move.} (7. exf6 {Natural move, but not the best.} Nxf6 8. O-O O-O 9. c4 {Logical, and now we have} (9. Re1 $4 {Natural, but losing!} Nc6 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Ge6e5] Big problems on f2, maybe e5 will be our next move. Evaluation is more than -2.} 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Rxe3 Ng4 12. Re2 e5 $19 {No good way to stop e4.}) 9... e5 $1 $146 {Very nice novelty, we can play for an advantage.} 10. Nxe5 Nc6 11. Nxc6 (11. Nf3 $2 Ng4 $17 {[%csl Rf2]}) 11... bxc6 {[%cal Gf6g4] very good compensation because we have Ng4 ideas.} 12. h3 {[%cal Rf6g4,Yh3g4] against Ng4, but} (12. Be3 Bxe3 13. fxe3 Qb6 14. Qd2 Re8 $11 {We will take back the pawn very soon.}) 12... Qd6 $36 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gc8h3,Gd6g3] and we have Bxh3 and Qg3 ideas. Sample line could be} 13. Kh1 Qe7 $1 {[%cal Gf6g4] Fanastic move, with Ng4 idea.} 14. cxd5 Ng4 15. Nc3 Nxf2+ 16. Rxf2 Bxf2 $13 {[%cal Ge7h4] Evaluation is balanced, but I am not sure White would be ready to play it.}) (7. a3 {is not logical now.} fxe5 8. Nxe5 Nf6 9. b4 Bd6 10. Bb2 a5 11. b5 Nbd7 $36 {Just a good version of the 5. a3 line.}) (7. Qe2 Nc6 8. O-O {Transposes to the main line.}) 7... Nc6 8. Qe2 $1 {Critical continuation.} (8. Re1 $2 {[%csl Rf2] very bad move because f2 is weak.} fxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Rxe5 Bxf2+ $1 $19 {[%cal Gd8f6] Small tactic, no compensation.}) (8. Bf4 {Logical move, but Black has a strong reply:} g5 $1 {Important move. If you think that Black is in danger, ask the same question to White and you will understand that also White is in danger.} ({Not} 8... fxe5 $6 9. Bxe5 $1 {And White is slightly better.} (9. Nxe5 $6 Qf6 $11) 9... Nf6 10. Bg3 O-O 11. c4 $14 {[%csl Gg3] It is the same position as seen under 7.exf6, but with a bishop on g3 instead of c1.}) 9. Be3 $1 {Only move.} (9. Bg3 $2 {natural, but bad.} f5 $1 {And now it's dangerous only for White.} 10. h3 Nh6 $17 {[%csl Rg3] Big positional advantage.}) 9... Bxe3 10. fxe3 f5 $1 {No problem, for example} 11. c4 {Logical move.} dxc4 12. Bxc4 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Ke7 $11 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg8h6,Gh6f7] Nh6-Nf7 next. Sometimes e5 can be weak.}) (8. Bb5 a6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 $132 {[%csl Bc5,Bc8][%cal Gd8c7,Gg8e7,Ge8g8] Ne7-Qc7-00 next. We have two bishops and a good position.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3a4,Gc1e3] White is playing for blockade.} Ba7 {[%cal Rc1e3,Gc6c5] Propylactic move.} (10... fxe5 {Also interesting to play for compensation.} 11. Nxe5 Nf6 12. Nxc6 Qc7 $44 {Development and compensation.}) 11. Na4 Qc7 12. Re1 Ne7 {Don't be afraid of exf6 move.} 13. Be3 (13. exf6 gxf6 14. Nh4 h5 $13 {[%cal Ge8f7] The king on f7 stays very well.}) 13... c5 14. exf6 gxf6 15. Nh4 h5 {To stop Qh5+.} 16. Qf3 {[%cal Re8f7,Ge3g5] Concrete line:} Qc6 $1 {Important tempo.} 17. Qxf6 $1 (17. b3 $2 e5 $17 {[%cal Gd5d4,Gc6f6] Black is strategically winning.}) 17... Rf8 18. Qh6 Qxa4 19. b4 $3 {Crazy position, but equal evaluation, with many moves for Black:} cxb4 {Natural.} 20. Ng6 Nxg6 21. Qxg6+ Rf7 22. Qg8+ {Repetition.} Rf8 23. Qg6+ Rf7 $11) (8. exf6 {harmless.} Nxf6 9. c4 dxc4 $1 {This move immediately solves all our problems.} (9... O-O 10. Nc3 {also playable for both.}) 10. Bxc4 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Ne4 $1 {[%csl Rf2] White's f2 pawn is weak.} 12. Rf1 Nd4 $11 {We have very active pieces.}) 8... fxe5 {I like the forced approach.} (8... Qc7 {possible, but not to my style.} 9. Bf4 Nge7 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Rae1 {White has a nice position, but also Black's is normal:} f5 12. Nb3 Bb6 $132 {Just position.}) 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Qxe5 Nf6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc5d6] Our idea is to continue with 00 and Bd6.} 11. Bf4 {[%cal Rc5d6] The most annoying move, against Bd6.} (11. c4 {Rare move.} O-O 12. Nc3 {Shirov-Agdestein.} Qb6 $5 {looks good, for example:} 13. cxd5 Bxf2+ $1 14. Kh1 Bd7 $1 $132 {[%cal Ga8e8] no problem.} (14... Bd4 $6 {Premature.} 15. Qe1 $1 exd5 $4 16. Nxd5 $1 {[%csl Rf8] is White's trap.} Nxd5 17. Bxh7+ Kxh7 18. Rxf8 $18 {That's why 14...Bd7 is important move.})) (11. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2f3] White wants Nf3.} O-O 12. Nf3 Bd6 13. Qe2 Qc7 {Black is ready for e5.} 14. Re1 {Only move.} (14. h3 $2 e5 $2 $17 {Big advantage.}) 14... Ng4 $5 {interesting.} (14... Bd7 {[%cal Ga8e8] Logical move, good position.} 15. Ne5 Be8 $11 {For people who play French, this is absolutely normal position.}) 15. h3 Nxf2 16. Qxf2 e5 $13 {No need to think about French, just interesting position. For example:} 17. Qd2 e4 18. Be2 exf3 19. Qxd5+ Kh8 20. Bxf3 {No pawn, but} Bxh3 $1 21. gxh3 Bb4 $11 {[%cal Gd5e5] Qe5 is the only move, and we go to an equal endgame.}) (11. Bb5+ {The most common move.} Kf7 {[%csl Gf7] Kf7 is not bad.} 12. Bf4 {against Bd6.} (12. Nd2 Bd6 $36 {[%cal Ga7a6,Ge6e5] Black has a lot of tempi.}) 12... Qb6 {[%csl Rb5,Rd4][%cal Rb6b5,Rc5d4] with tempo.} 13. Qe2 {Only move.} a6 14. Bd3 e5 $1 {Very strong move, to finish development.} (14... Qxb2 $6 {Now this is dangerous.} 15. Nd2 $40 {[%cal Gd2f3] No development.}) 15. Qxe5 {White wants to sacrifice material.} (15. Bxe5 {was played in the game Eggleston-Shatil, Rilton Cup 2024.} Re8 16. Kh1 Bg4 17. f3 Bh5 18. Qe1 {So far, White played only moves, to not lose the e5 bishop.} Rxe5 {Forced operation.} 19. Qxe5 Bd4 20. Qf4 Bxb2 21. Nd2 Bxa1 22. Rxa1 Bg6 {And it's just an equal position.} 23. Rb1 (23. Bxg6+ hxg6 $15) 23... Qc6 24. Nb3 Re8 $11 {Playable, both kings are not ideal, balanced game.}) 15... Bd4 16. Qg5 Bxb2 17. Be5 $1 {The best, and now we don't take, because the bishop is already on the diagonal.} (17. Nd2 $6 {This way, we can accept:} Bxa1 18. Rxa1 Re8 19. Nf3 Kg8 $132 {I understand White's compensation, but material is material.}) 17... Bxe5 {This is simple.} (17... Bxa1 $6 18. Bxa1 $40 {[%csl Ga1,Rf7][%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f3] Position could be dangerous for Black.}) 18. Qxe5 Re8 $11 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ga8c8,Gf7g8] Bd7-Kg8-Rac8 next. Equal position.}) 11... O-O 12. Bg3 $1 {[%csl Gg3] Best prophylactic move. Black has 2 options now:} (12. Nd2 $2 {Just bad.} Ng4 $1 $19 {[%csl Rf2] White is lost.}) (12. h3 {a bit slow.} Qb6 $1 $13 {[%csl Rb2,Rf2][%cal Gc5d4] A lot of targets.}) 12... Ng4 $5 {Interesting idea.} (12... g6 {[%cal Gf6h5] Standard move, with the idea Nh5.} 13. c4 {Critical move.} (13. Nd2 {Normal development is not scary for Black.} Nh5 14. Nf3 Nxg3 15. Qxg3 Qf6 {Black's position is normal, for example:} 16. Ne5 (16. c3 Qf4 {also typical idea.} 17. Qxf4 Rxf4 $11 {Equal endgame.}) 16... b5 $5 {Take some space.} 17. Rae1 (17. Bxb5 Bd6 $36 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ga8b8] Black will regain b2, with initiative.}) 17... b4 $11 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gc5d4,Gf6f4] No improvement for White, Black's pieces work from their initial position.}) (13. h3 $2 {Mistake.} Nh5 14. Bh2 Qh4 $40 {Black's attack is very strong.}) 13... Ng4 $5 {More interesting, for complicated game.} (13... Nh5 {possible, but unpractical.} 14. Nc3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 {Black has problems with d5 pawn.} Qd6 {We can go to endgame, it's objectively normal, but after} 16. Qxd6 Bxd6 17. cxd5 exd5 18. Nxd5 Be6 $11 {In theory, Black is fine, but in practice, it can be a bit unpleasant.}) 14. Qe2 e5 {Concrete line:} 15. h3 Nxf2 16. Bxf2 Rxf2 17. Rxf2 e4 {Rook down, but position is interesting:} 18. Bxe4 {Critical move.} (18. Bc2 $2 {Logical, but mistake:} Qg5 $1 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gc8h3] Important move, and White has problems with the king.} 19. Kh1 Qg3 $17 {[%csl Rf2,Rh2][%cal Gc5f2,Gc5d6] Black's attack is very strong.}) 18... dxe4 19. Nc3 {White gives back all the extra material, but we don't take it immediately, because it gives White a big positional advantage.} Bf5 $1 {Development first.} 20. Rd1 Qg5 21. Kh2 Bxf2 {Now we take.} 22. Qxf2 e3 23. Qf3 Be6 $11 {Evaluation is equal.}) 13. Qh5 {Logical, with tempo.} (13. Qe2 {is met with} h5 $1 {Important idea.} 14. h3 h4 $1 {This reaction is good here.} 15. Qxg4 hxg3 16. Qxg3 {And Black has very good compensation after} Bd6 17. Qg6 Qh4 18. Nd2 Bd7 {We play for 3 results, with a good position.} 19. Rae1 Rf6 20. Qg4 Qxg4 21. hxg4 e5 $11 {Full compensation, a lot of ideas left in the position.}) 13... Nf6 {We are ready to repeat.} 14. Qe2 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2] Tempo move.} 15. Nd2 {Critical line.} (15. Be5 {defends b2, but we can play tricky:} Nd7 (15... Bd4 {also not too bad, but a bit passive.} 16. Nd2 Bxe5 17. Qxe5 Nd7 $1 $13 {But I think 15... Nd7 is a more interesting line for us.}) 16. Qh5 Nf6 $1 {Only move.} 17. Bxf6 (17. Qh4 h6 {Now h6, and again we are ready for Nd7.} 18. Nd2 Nd7 $13 {[%cal Ge6e5,Re5c3] White must sacrifice a pawn, unclear position.}) 17... Rxf6 18. Qxh7+ Kf7 19. Qh5+ Ke7 {And Black is okay:} 20. Qg5 Bxf2+ 21. Kh1 Kf8 22. Nd2 Qe3 23. Nf3 Bd7 $11 {Equal position.}) 15... Qxb2 {We accept the pawn, and White has compensation, but position is playable and for 3 results:} 16. Nb3 Qa3 17. Nxc5 Qxc5 18. c4 Bd7 19. cxd5 exd5 20. Rac1 Qa3 $11 {Equal position, but Black still has extra pawn, solid pieces. All could happen here in a real game.} *

