{[%evp 0,32,14,16,61,45,45,36,36,36,36,20,36,23,47,42,35,29,19,7,6,-17,-4,-2,25,28,28,11,11,-12,5,6,13,13,24]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 e6 5. Bd3 $5 {Tricky move order.} Nd7 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Re5][%cal Gd7e5,Gd7c5]} ({Don't play} 5... Bxc5 $2 {because after} 6. Qg4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rg7] Black doesn't have a good reaction to defend g7.}) 6. Nf3 {White must defend e5.} Nxc5 {[%csl Gc5,Yd3][%cal Yc5d3] We capture on c5 with the knight, particularly because White's bishop is on d3.} 7. O-O {Most common continuation.} (7. Be3 Bd7 8. O-O Nxd3 9. cxd3 Ne7 $11 {Sanal-Abasov, 2023.}) (7. Bb5+ Bd7 $11 {no problem of course.}) (7. Be2 {White tries to save the bishops.} Ne7 8. O-O a6 $5 $146 {A useful move. We hold off on Nc6 for now—sometimes we can go for Nf5 instead (especially after Be3), and in other cases, Ng6 might be an option as well.} (8... Nc6 9. c4 (9. Be3 {also possible, and could be tricky.}) 9... d4 {tricky position, White has a lot of options but Black is fine.} (9... dxc4 10. Qxd8+ {worse endgame compared to 8...a6.})) 9. c4 {looks critical, but we are absolutely fine after} (9. Be3 $6 Nf5 $15 {[%csl Re3,Gf5] that's why we wait for Nc6!}) (9. c3 Bd7 {another useful move: we wait Be3.} 10. Nbd2 Ng6 $132 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gd8c7] Qc7 next and no problem.}) (9. Re1 Bd7 {[%csl Gd7] Once again, we delay committing our knight to a specific square. If needed, we also have another useful waiting move: Rc8.} 10. Nc3 (10. Nbd2 Ng6 $132 {[%csl Gg6]}) 10... Nf5 $11 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Rb1d2,Rd2b3,Rb3d4] now Nf5 is good because no Nbd2-Nb3-Nd4 plan.}) 9... dxc4 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bxc4 b5 $1 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7] Bb7 next and no problem.}) 7... Nxd3 {We want to see how White recaptures before deciding on the best way to continue our development.} 8. Qxd3 {I am more concerned about 8.Qxd3, as I can already visualize some scenarios where White could develop an attack.} (8. cxd3 {less dangerous for us.} Ne7 9. Nc3 Nf5 $1 $146 {[%csl Yd3,Gf5] in the cxd3 structure, I think that f5 is the best square for our knight.} (9... Nc6 {also possible, but less interesting.} 10. Bg5 Qb6 11. Rb1 Bd7 $132) 10. Bf4 (10. Bg5 Qb6 $132 {[%cal Gc8d7]}) 10... Bd7 $132 {no problem.}) 8... Ne7 9. Re1 $5 {GM Demchenko played it a few days ago, and it means that this is serious!} (9. c4 {direct move.} dxc4 10. Qxc4 (10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] b6-Bb7 next. Good endgame.}) 10... Bd7 $1 {[%csl Bd7] important move.} (10... Nc6 $2 {natural but bad. Our knight should commit to c6!} 11. Nc3 Be7 12. Qg4 $16) 11. Nc3 Rc8 12. Qe2 (12. Qg4 Ng6 $15 {[%cal Gd8b6,Bd8a5] already slightly better for Black. Qa5 or Qb6 next.}) 12... Nf5 {[%cal Gf8b4] probably Bb4 next, for example:} 13. Rd1 Bb4 14. Bg5 Qb6 $11 {no problem, and we can play for three results.}) 9... Bd7 $146 {[%csl Gd7,Ye7] most useful move. We will develop our Ne7 only later, according to White's next move.} 10. Nbd2 (10. Be3 $6 Nf5 $1 $15 {as always.}) (10. Nc3 a6 $1 {we stop the important Ne2-Ned4 plan:} 11. Ne2 Bb5 12. Qd1 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Rc8 $132 {[%cal Cd8c7,Cc7c4] I prefer Black. Maybe Qc7-Qc4 next.}) 10... Ng6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gf7f6] we just want to play Be7-00-f6.} (10... Nf5 $6 {not a good move now:} 11. Nb3 Be7 12. c3 O-O 13. Bf4 a5 14. Nbd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 $40 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Ge1e3] attacking chances (Qb3, or Re3-Rh3, or Re3-Rg3).}) 11. g3 {For many people, playing g3 when Black puts a knight on g6 is like drinking coffee in the morning.} (11. Nb3 {too slow:} Be7 12. g3 f6 $1 $132 {Now we are in time to successfully deal with} 13. h4 Qc7 14. exf6 gxf6 15. h5 Ne5 $15 {[%csl Rb3,Yc7,Ge5] and this is thanks to the Nb3-Qc7 inclusion!}) 11... Ne7 $5 {My idea is a bit unusual, but after provoking g3, we can return to the Nf5 plan—this time in an improved version!} (11... f6 $2 12. exf6 gxf6 13. Qxd5 $16 {[%csl Gd5] big difference.}) (11... Be7 $2 12. h4 $1 f6 13. exf6 gxf6 14. h5 $16 {[%csl Rg6]}) (11... Qb6 $5 {deserves attention, but it's not my recommendation.} 12. Nb3 f6 13. exf6 (13. Be3 Qa6 $1 14. Qxa6 bxa6 15. Bd4 Kf7 $11 {equal endgame.}) 13... gxf6 14. Qxd5 Be7 15. Qh5 e5 $44 {full compensation, but we need to play without a pawn.}) 12. Nb3 Nf5 13. c3 Be7 {our position is just good, and we should compare it with the 10...Nf5 variation.} 14. Bf4 a5 15. Nbd4 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 O-O $132 {[%csl Rg3] Pawn g3 is bad because it reduces White's attacking chances—no Re3-Rg3/Rh3, no Qg3 ideas...} *

