{[%evp 0,30,21,31,57,55,48,41,53,53,53,26,32,-1,0,36,-7,17,12,7,19,12,66,70,59,35,35,31,23,24,28,20,15]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 e6 5. Qg4 {White provokes h5.} (5. a3 $5 Bxc5 $1 6. Qg4 {concrete line, here you need to memorize some lines.} (6. b4 Be7 7. Qg4 {less interesting now because of} g6 8. Nf3 a5 $1 {We provoke b5, and our knight will have the c5 square.} 9. b5 (9. bxa5 {very rare.} Nc6 $1 10. Bd3 f6 11. Bb2 fxe5 12. Nxe5 Bf6 $132 {equal, for example:} 13. Qe2 (13. f4 Nh6 14. Qh3 Nf5 $132 {equal fighting position.}) 13... Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Nxe5 15. Qxe5 Qf6 $11) 9... Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Yf1d3] whenever White plays Bd3, we can continue with Nc5.} 10. Bd3 (10. c4 $6 {Lobanov.} f6 $1 $15) 10... h5 $1 {important move to include.} (10... f6 $2 11. Qh3 $1 $16 {[%csl Rg6]}) 11. Qf4 Nh6 $132 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gd7c5,Gh6f5] b6-Bb7-Nc5-Nf5, sometimes g5. Very interesting position for Black.}) 6... Ne7 $1 {we sacrifice g7.} (6... g6 $6 {now it's not so good.} 7. Nf3 $14 {[%cal Rb8d7,Rd7c5] not easy for our knight to go to c5.}) 7. Nf3 {the main move, and here you really need to remember.} (7. Qxg7 {important mention, but it's not critical.} Rg8 8. Qxh7 Nbc6 $44 {better version than Winawer!}) (7. b4 h5 $1 {[%csl Bh5] important inclusion.} (7... Bb6 $6 8. Bb2 $14) 8. Qd1 {[%cal Rc5d4] necessary against Bd4.} (8. Qxg7 $2 Rg8 9. Qh7 Bd4 $1 10. Ra2 Bxe5 $15) (8. Qg5 Bb6 (8... Bd4 $2 {no sense now.} 9. c3 $16) 9. Nf3 Ng6 $15 {Lobanov-Dudin, 2021.}) 8... Bb6 9. Nf3 a5 10. Bb2 $1 (10. b5 $6 {most common move, but positionally bad.} Nd7 11. Bd3 (11. Bb2 Nc5 $15 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc8d7,Ge7g6] Bd7-Ng6 next. Sometimes a4.}) 11... Nxe5 $1 12. Nxe5 Bd4 13. Nxf7 Kxf7 14. Ra2 Bf6 15. O-O e5 $15 {Fernandez-Bartel, 2024.}) 10... axb4 11. axb4 Rxa1 12. Bxa1 Nbc6 13. b5 Na7 $11 {[%cal Gc8d7,Yb6a5] Bd7-Ba5 normal position.}) ({or} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Nf3 {transposes in 7.Nf3.}) 7... O-O 8. Bd3 {most common continuation.} (8. b4 $5 {modern continuation.} Bb6 9. Bd3 (9. Bb2 Ng6 {[%cal Gf7f6] we are ready for f6.} 10. h4 {very good try for White because Black needs to be precise.} (10. Bd3 {trans in 9.Bd3.}) 10... f6 $1 11. exf6 Rxf6 12. h5 Rf4 13. Qg3 Bc7 $1 14. Qg5 Qxg5 15. Nxg5 Ne5 16. h6 Rf5 $13 {unclear, but I continued to analyze the first line shown by the engine, and it's very interesting:} 17. Nxh7 Kxh7 18. hxg7+ Kxg7 19. Bd3 Rf7 20. f4 Nbd7 21. fxe5 Bxe5 22. Nc3 a5 23. O-O-O axb4 24. axb4 Rf4 $11) 9... Ng6 10. Bb2 (10. O-O f5 11. exf6 Qxf6 $132 {no problem.}) 10... f5 11. exf6 e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] key move.} 12. Qh5 e4 13. Ng5 Bxf2+ $1 14. Kd1 (14. Kxf2 Rxf6+ 15. Bxf6 Qxf6+ 16. Ke1 exd3 17. Qxh7+ Kf8 18. Rf1 Bf5 19. Qh5 Kg8 20. Qh7+ $11 {draw.}) 14... Rxf6 15. Qxh7+ Kf8 16. Be2 (16. Qh5 Kg8 17. Qh7+ Kf8 $11 {just repetition.}) 16... Nc6 17. Rf1 e3 $1 {very complicated position.} 18. b5 {engine's first move.} (18. h4 $2 d4 19. h5 Qd5 20. hxg6 Qxg5 21. Qh8+ Ke7 22. Qxg7+ Kd6 23. Nc3 dxc3 24. Bxc3 Rxg6 25. Qf8+ Kc7 $19 {Nemeth-Doric, 2019.}) 18... Nce5 19. Bxe5 Nxe5 20. Qh8+ Ke7 21. Qxg7+ Kd6 22. Nc3 Rf5 23. Qh6+ Rf6 24. Qg7 Rf5 $11) 8... f5 $1 9. exf6 {Concrete option.} (9. Qg3 {[%cal Gh2h4] Positional option. White is ready for h4, and we need to play the super prophylactic move} Ng6 $1 {[%csl Bg6] key move.} 10. b4 (10. h4 $6 Qc7 11. h5 f4 $17 {[%csl Re5,Gf4][%cal Yg6e5] Nxe5 next.}) (10. O-O Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gc5e7,Gd7c5] Be7-Nc5 next. no problem.}) (10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Ne2 (11. O-O $2 f4 12. Qh3 Nd4 $1 $17) 11... Qc7 12. Bf4 Bd7 13. O-O Nxf4 14. Qxf4 Be8 $132 {[%cal Ge8h5] Bh5 next and no problem.}) 10... Be7 11. Bb2 (11. h4 $6 Qc7 12. h5 $2 f4 $1 $19 {[%csl Bf4] again key idea.}) 11... a5 12. b5 Nd7 13. h4 Nc5 14. h5 Nh8 $132 {interesting balanced position.}) 9... Rxf6 10. Qh5 (10. Bg5 {concrete line for draw.} e5 $1 11. Qh4 e4 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Qxf6 (13. Ng5 fxg5 14. Qxg5+ Kh8 15. Qf6+ Kg8 16. Qg5+ $11 {just draw.}) (13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Qxe4 Bf5 15. Qxb7 Nbc6 $36) 13... exd3 14. Qg5+ (14. cxd3 $2 Qf8 $17) 14... Kh8 15. Qf6+ (15. cxd3 $2 Qg8) 15... Kg8 $11 {just repetition.}) (10. Qh4 $6 h6 11. O-O Nbc6 12. c4 {Karjakin-Wei, 2019.} Qe8 $1 13. Nc3 (13. Nbd2 a5 $17) 13... Rxf3 14. gxf3 Ne5 $17) 10... h6 11. O-O (11. b4 {doesn't have independent value:} Bd6 12. Bb2 Nd7 $1 13. O-O (13. Bxf6 $4 Nxf6 14. Qh4 e5 $19) 13... e5 {transposes in 11.00.}) 11... Bd6 $1 {important prophylactic against b4 move: we see White's reaction, and then we decide how to develop our knight.} (11... Nbc6 $6 12. b4 $1 Bd6 13. Bb2 $16) (11... Nd7 $6 12. Nc3 $1 Bd6 13. Bg5 Rf7 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Rae1 $16) 12. Bd2 (12. c4 Nbc6 13. Nc3 Bd7 14. cxd5 Be8 15. Qh3 exd5 $11) (12. b4 Nd7 $1 13. Bb2 e5 $13) 12... Nbc6 13. Bc3 e5 14. Nxe5 {Grebnev-Bodrogi, 2024.} d4 $1 15. Nxc6 Nxc6 16. Bb4 Bxb4 $1 {we want to recapture with the knight on b4.} 17. axb4 Nxb4 18. Be4 Qf8 {[%cal Gc8f5] Bf5 next and no problem.} 19. c3 Bf5 $1 $11) 5... h5 6. Qf4 (6. Qg3 $6 {Ponkratov played it in many games, but Black is fine:} h4 7. Qg4 (7. Qc3 d4 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 8. Qc4 (8. Qb3 Bxc5 $36) 8... Nc6 9. Nf3 Rh5 $1 $15) 7... Nh6 $1 8. Bxh6 Rxh6 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. Bb5 Rg6 11. Qh3 Bxc5 $15) 6... Bxc5 7. Bd3 (7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Nf3 {transposes in 7.Nc3.} Qa5 $5 $146 {[%cal Ga5b4]} 9. Bd2 Qb4 $11 {no problem.}) (7. Nf3 {White invites us for Qb6.} Nc6 (7... Qb6 {interesting but after} 8. Bd3 $1 Bxf2+ 9. Ke2 Bc5 10. Nc3 Bd7 $13 {the position is very complicated.}) 8. Bd3 (8. Nc3 {transposes in 7.Nc3.}) 8... f6 {transposes in 7.Bd3.}) 7... Nc6 8. Nf3 f6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] very important move. transposes in 7.Bd3.} (8... Nb4 $6 9. O-O Nxd3 10. cxd3 $14 {difficult to play for Black.}) 9. Qg3 $1 {important prophylactic move.} (9. Bg6+ $6 Kf8 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gg8e7] Nge7 next and we win a tempo against Bg6.} 10. O-O Nge7 11. Bd3 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bd6 $19) (9. O-O $6 g5 $1 10. Bg6+ Kf8 $19) 9... Qc7 {safest continuation.} (9... Kf8 {also good.} 10. exf6 gxf6 (10... Nxf6 {for the engine it's dubious, but if we go deeper this is also fine.} 11. O-O e5 $1 $13) 11. Nh4 Nge7 $13 {Ne5 next maybe, or Kf7. Just interesting fighting position.}) 10. O-O g5 $5 11. exf6 {White has nothing better than this, but after} Qxg3 12. hxg3 g4 {the endgame is very fine for us.} 13. Nh4 Nxf6 14. Be3 b6 15. Nd2 Kf7 $11 {Even though Qg4 lines are a bit annoyin and they require some theoretical knowledge, Black achieves a safe and solid position. If you understand the key ideas, you will have no trouble reaching a comfortable game.} *

