{[%evp 0,50,14,31,57,57,49,53,53,28,54,31,28,28,65,60,60,74,74,74,74,74,74,74,74,75,75,75,87,78,71,79,83,66,90,90,111,72,73,65,67,67,53,57,57,77,73,54,54,54,54,43,51]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 ({We need to compare this variation with} 3... Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. c3 {By playing 3...c5 4.c3, White aims to transpose into this position, but we are not forced to accept this fate!}) 4. c3 {A sideline that has become very popular nowadays. White usually chooses this move if, in his repertoire against 3...Bf5, he continues with 4.Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6.c3. By playing 4.c3 against our 3...c5, White aims to transpose into the same setup he uses against 3...Bf5, allowing him to prepare just one system against the Caro-Kann instead of studying multiple variations.} Nc6 5. Be2 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Rc8g4] White's most interesting move order, and it was suggested by GM Anish Giri. By starting with 5.Be2, White prevents Black's Bg4 options.} (5. f4 $2 {positional mistake.} cxd4 $1 {necessary move because after 5.f3, White's threat was dxc5.} 6. cxd4 h5 $5 {[%csl Yf5,Yg4][%cal Gc8g4] A useful move. We don’t play 6...Bf5 immediately, as our bishop could also be developed to g4.} 7. Nc3 (7. Nf3 Bg4 $1 $15 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8h6] e6-Nh6 next, Black is already preferable.}) 7... Bf5 {positional option.} (7... Bg4 $5 {concrete option.} 8. Qb3 Nxd4 9. Qxb7 Rh6 $1 $36 {[%cal Gh6b6] Rb6 next, and this looks very interesting.}) 8. Nf3 (8. Qb3 Nxd4 9. Qxb7 Rh6 $1 $36 {[%cal Gh6b6] Rb6 next.} 10. Bb5+ Nxb5 11. Qxb5+ Bd7 12. Qxd5 Rg6 $36 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gd7c6,Gg8h6,Ge7e6] This is not compensation, but initiative. We can continue with Bc6 next, or Nh6, or just e6.}) 8... e6 9. Be2 Nh6 $15 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Be7-00 next. This is just a very good version of a typical Caro-Kann position.}) (5. Bb5 {rare move.} cxd4 (5... Qa5 $5 {[%cal Gc5d4] also deserves attention, with the idea cxd4.}) 6. cxd4 Bf5 $11 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8e7] e6-Nge7 next, and no problems for Black. With the bishop on b5, White's only idea is Bxc6+ at some point, but it doesn't create any positional problem.}) (5. Be3 $5 {This move is very interesting because Black has only one good continuation!} Nh6 $1 {[%csl Gh6] If we don't play 5...Nh6, White will be better, so it's worth remembering this one!} 6. Bd3 (6. Bxh6 $6 {positionally dubious.} gxh6 7. Nf3 Qb6 $15) (6. Nf3 Nf5 $132 {[%csl Re3] no problem, maybe even some initiative for us.}) 6... Nf5 7. Ne2 $5 {engine's recommendation, but we have nothing to worry about after} Nxe3 8. fxe3 g6 9. O-O Bg4 {my recommendation. First we exchange White's knight, and then we will castle.} (9... Bh6 {engine's move, but after} 10. Nf4 O-O 11. Na3 {[%csl Gf4] I like White's knight on f4.}) 10. h3 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 Bh6 12. Nd2 {logical continuation.} O-O 13. Nf3 f6 $11 {no problem.}) (5. Nf3 {[%cal Gc8g4] harmless move order because Black can now develop the bishop to g4.} cxd4 ({But not} 5... Bg4 $6 {immediately because of} 6. dxc5 $1 $14) 6. cxd4 Bg4 $1 {A lot of games here, but Black is already fine.} 7. Be2 e6 8. O-O (8. Nbd2 $6 {positional inaccuracy.} Bb4 $1 9. O-O Bxd2 10. Qxd2 Nge7 $36 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8b6,Gg4f3,Ge7f5] Bxf3-Qb6-Nf5 next, with a huge pressure against d4.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge7f5,Ge7c8] What is our plan: Nf5 or Nc8 next, and then just Be7-00.} 9. Nbd2 {[%cal Yd2f3] Most common continuation. White’s idea is to recapture with the knight on f3 if Black decides to play Bxf3.} (9. Nc3 Nf5 10. Be3 Bb4 $36 {[%csl Gb4] but now b4 is a very good square for our bishop.}) (9. Be3 {invites} Nf5 {[%csl Gf5]} 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. h3 Bh5 12. Rc1 (12. g4 $2 {very bad of corse:} Nxe3 13. fxe3 Bg6 $17) 12... O-O 13. a3 a5 {[%cal Rb2b4] useful move against b4.} 14. Qb3 Qb8 $5 $15 {[%cal Gb8a7] Qa7-Rc8 next.}) 9... a5 $5 $146 {[%csl Ga5] My recommendation is to play the useful a5 move.} (9... Nf5 $2 {this authomatic and very common move is a mistake now!} 10. h3 $1 $14 {[%cal Rg4h5,Gg2g4] and we don't have Bh5 because of g4.}) (9... Nc8 {not a bad move, but White gets some ideas like} 10. h3 Bh5 11. Nb3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ga1c1,Gb3c5] Be3-Rc1-Nc5 next. It's equal for the engine, but White has easy play.}) 10. h3 {White can include h3 in any moment.} Bh5 {and now, let's imagine that White also plays a waiting move like} 11. a3 Nc8 {only now we play it.} 12. Nb1 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc3b5] logical idea of the engine: Nc3-Nb5 next.} (12. Nb3 $2 {this was an interesting plan with the pawns on a7 and a2, but here it's a mistake:} Bxf3 13. Bxf3 a4 $1 $17 {[%csl Rb3]}) 12... Bxf3 $1 {immediately kills the game.} (12... Qb6 $5 {is also fine if you want to have a game.} 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nc3 Be7 $13 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf7f5] 00-f5 next. Engine's evaluation is 0.00, because it's too unclear even for him!}) 13. Bxf3 Qb6 $1 14. Be3 Qxb2 {[%cal Rb1c3] No Nc3.} 15. Nd2 Be7 16. Rb1 Qxa3 17. Ra1 {the game now ends in a strange moves repetition:} (17. Rxb7 $6 O-O $15 {[%csl Ga5] extra pawn and White doesn't have full compensation.}) 17... Qd3 18. Be2 Qg6 19. Bh5 $1 $11 {we cannot escape the draw, but White has to force it.}) 5... cxd4 $5 {My recommendation. I like it because it leads to a very simple equality, without the need to memorize many lines.} ({we can also play} 5... Bf5 6. Nf3 e6 {but this would transpose in the 3...Bf5 Caro-Kann. If we want to play 3...c5, it's better to keep it independent, in my opinion.}) 6. cxd4 Qb6 $5 {[%csl Rd4] immediately putting pressure against d4.} (6... Bf5 {is always a possible alternative.}) 7. Nc3 $1 {critical move.} ({After the natural} 7. Nf3 {Black has} Bg4 $132 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8e7] e6-Nge7 and no problem. Maybe it's even easier to play this from the Black's side.}) 7... Qxd4 {only 10 games here, but this is the simplest solution against the 4.c3 Nc6 5.Be2!? tricky line.} ({Of course, we don't want to play} 7... e6 $2 8. Nf3 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Rc8] Because we would be stuck with the problematic Bc8, while White gets an improved version of the Advance French, thanks to his knight being on c3.}) 8. Nxd5 (8. Qxd4 $146 {is less dangerous because after} Nxd4 9. Nxd5 Rb8 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gd4c2] White also needs to think about Nc2+.} 10. Bd3 {the strongest move, according to the engine.} (10. Be3 {engine's second best.} Nc2+ 11. Kd2 Nxe3 ({not} 11... Nxa1 $4 12. Bxa7 $18 {[%cal Gd5c7]}) 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14. Nxe3 e6 $11 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gg8e7,Gh8d8] Bc5 (or Bb4+) -Ne7 next, with an equal endgame.}) 10... Bf5 {it's good for us to exchange the bishops.} 11. Bxf5 Nxf5 12. Nf3 e6 13. Nc7+ Kd7 14. Nb5 a6 15. Nc3 h5 $1 {[%csl Gf5,Gh5] we consolidate our Nf5, so that White doesn't have g2-g4 options.} 16. Ke2 Nge7 17. Rd1+ Ke8 $11 {[%cal Ge7c6,Gf8e7] just Nc6-Be7 next, with easy equality.}) 8... Qxd1+ 9. Bxd1 Rb8 $1 {this is the critical position, but there are only 4 games.} ({we don't want to play} 9... Kd8 $2 {Because we are ready to give up castling rights ONLY if White wastes time for Nc7+.} 10. Nf3 $16) 10. Nf3 $1 $146 {critical continuation, and it's a Novelty.} (10. f4 {not dangerous.} Bf5 11. Be3 {engine's recommendation.} (11. Nf3 e6 12. Nc7+ (12. Ne3 Be4 $11) 12... Kd7 13. Nb5 a6 14. Nc3 Bb4 $132 {[%cal Gg8e7] Nge7 next. Don't think that this is just a draw, once we develop our pieces, we can also try to play ambitiously.}) 11... e6 12. Nc7+ {only continuation that poses some problems.} Kd7 13. Nb5 a6 14. Nc3 Nge7 {important move, because after} (14... Bb4 {less precise now because of} 15. Bf3 $1 $14) 15. Bf3 {we have} g5 $1 16. fxg5 Nxe5 $11 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gf8g7] and our bishop goes to g7.}) (10. Bf4 {[%csl Rf4] most common continuation, it was played in 3/4 games, but Bf4 is misplaced.} e6 11. Nc7+ Kd8 12. Nb5 Bb4+ $36 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gg8e7] Nge7 next, and the engine already slightly prefers Black because Bf4 is very misplaced.}) 10... e6 11. Nc7+ {only critical direction.} (11. Nc3 Bb4 $11 {[%cal Gg8e7] Nge7 next and, as always, no problems for Black.}) 11... Kd7 12. Nb5 Bb4+ 13. Ke2 $1 {[%cal Gd1a4,Gh1d1] White hopes on Ba4-Rd1.} (13. Bd2 $6 {positional mistake.} Bxd2+ 14. Kxd2 Nh6 $15 {[%cal Gd7e7] Ke7 next and it's slightly better for Black.}) 13... a6 $1 {the most precise way.} (13... Nge7 $6 14. Ba4 $14 {[%cal Gh1d1] Rd1 next, and it could be unpleasant. Still, if you go deeper with the engine, White's advantage decreases after some moves:} a6 15. Rd1+ Nd5 16. Nbd4 Kc7 17. Be3 Bd7 18. Rac1 Be7 $1 {[%cal Rf3g5] important move against Ng5.} 19. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2a5] with the idea Ba5+.} Kb6 20. Nxc6 Bxc6 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. Rc4 Rhc8 $14 {White only has a very small symbolic advantage.}) 14. a3 $1 {only critical continuation, and now Black must decide.} (14. Nbd4 {harmless.} Nxd4+ 15. Nxd4 Ne7 $11 {[%cal Gh8d8,Gd7e8] Rd8-Ke8 next and it's equal.}) (14. Nc3 Nge7 $132 {[%cal Ge7g6] Ng6 next.}) 14... Bc5 $5 {My recommendation. We don't want to play against the two bishops.} (14... axb5 15. axb4 Nge7 {this is good, according to the engine, but not everybody will be ready to play against the two bishops.} 16. Be3 $1 b6 17. Bd2 Bb7 18. Bc2 Nd5 $14 {/= slightly unpleasant, but very close to equal.}) 15. Nc3 (15. b4 {now it's different:} axb5 (15... Bxb4 16. axb4 axb5 $11 {also good, at least now we have an extra pawn, but White has compensation of course.}) 16. bxc5 Nge7 $11 {[%cal Gb8a8] Also here White has two bishops, but the situation is different: Black has very easy play and a solid position.}) 15... Nge7 {We just want to finish our development.} (15... Nd4+ {I am not sure about it because of} 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Ba4+ Ke7 {[%csl Rg8]} 18. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Rg8] difficult to develop Ng8, but also this is close to equal after} Bxc3 19. bxc3 Bd7 20. Bxd7 Kxd7 $14 {White will press, but objectively it's a draw.}) 16. Ne4 {What we need to understand is that if White doesn't follow the engine's first line, the position will immediately be equal, giving us easy play.} (16. Ba4 Rd8 17. Rd1+ Ke8 $11 {[%cal Gc8d7] Bd7 next and no problem.}) 16... Ba7 17. Bb3 $1 {[%cal Re7d5,Gb3d5] against Nd5.} (17. Bc2 Nd5 18. Rd1 h6 $1 $11 {[%csl Yh6][%cal Gd7e7,Rc1g5,Yh6g5] important move because we want to play Ke7, but we don't want to allow Bg5+.}) 17... Rd8 $1 18. Rd1+ (18. Nd6 {important line to remember:} Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd7e7] we must sacrifice f7.} 19. Nxf7 {if White doesn't take it, we just play Ke7.} Rf8 20. N7g5 h6 $1 21. Nxe6 {only move.} (21. Ne4 $4 {is not possible because of} Rxf3 $1 $19 {[%cal Gc6d4] followed by Nd4+.}) 21... Kxe6 22. Rd1 Nce7 23. Be3 Ra8 $13 {It's a new position, evaluated with the classical "0.00" by the engine, but it's White who needs to demonstrate something.} (23... Bxe3 $4 24. fxe3 $18 {[%cal Ge3e4] e4 next.})) 18... Ke8 19. Rxd8+ {engine's first move.} (19. Nd6+ $5 Kf8 {[%cal Ge7f5] just Nf5 next and it's equal.} 20. Ng5 {only interesting try for White.} Nxe5 {concrete.} (20... Nf5 {maybe simpler.} 21. Nxh7+ (21. Ngxf7 $2 Ncd4+ $19) 21... Kg8 22. Nxf5 Rxd1 23. Kxd1 Kxh7 24. Nd6 Bxf2 (24... Nxe5 $6 25. Bf4 $14) 25. Nxf7 Nd4 $44 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc8d7] Bd7 next, and full compensation thanks to the active pieces.}) 21. f4 N5c6 22. Ngxf7 Nf5 $1 23. Nxd8 Ncd4+ 24. Kd3 Nxd6 25. Be3 $1 {only move.} N6f5 26. Bxd4 Nxd4 27. Kc3 $1 Ne2+ 28. Kb4 Nd4 $11 {no improvement for White, and according to the engine the game will end in a repetition.}) 19... Nxd8 20. Nd6+ Kf8 {[%cal Gd8c6,Ge7g6] we just want to play Ndc6-Ng6.} 21. Be3 {only interesting move for White. If not 21.Be3, it's immediately "0.00".} Bxe3 22. Kxe3 Bd7 23. Ng5 h6 24. Nge4 Bc6 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gd8b7] our plan could be b6-Nb7.} 25. Rc1 b6 $11 {[%cal Gd8b7] just Nb7 next. At the start of the endgame, after 10.Nf3 (a novelty), the engine evaluation was +0.30, but now it has dropped to 0.00! Of course, it's extremely unlikely that your opponent will play this endgame with such precision, but I wanted to ensure that we are never worse and that, even against the best moves, we can fully equalize. In a real game, when you play 7...Qxd4, I am confident that you will get a balanced and playable position over the board. In my opinion, this is a very practical solution against the tricky 4.c3 Nc6 5.Be2!? line suggested by Anish Giri.} *

