{[%evp 0,39,14,31,57,57,48,48,53,0,2,-4,-19,-13,4,14,14,-44,-44,-44,-2,20,26,26,26,-59,19,19,23,23,26,19,1,20,16,-13,0,0,10,47,27,27]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 {Let's begin the first chapter by analyzing White's various options on move 4.} 4. Ne2 {this is probably White's most interesting minor sideline.} (4. c4 {doesn't have independent value, because after} cxd4 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Nxd4 {transposes in the 4.Nf3 cxd4 5.Nxd4 variation.}) (4. f4 {[%csl Rf4] too slow, and Black immediately solves the problems in more than one way.} cxd4 5. Nf3 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Gg4] when we have the chance, Bg4 is a very good way to develop.} 6. Nbd2 {only move for White to maintain equality.} e6 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Nxf3 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Ne7 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6] Nbc6 next, and no problems.}) (4. Bb5+ {only helps us:} Bd7 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 6. c3 (6. Nf3 $6 cxd4 7. Nxd4 e6 8. O-O Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 $15 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7g6,Gf8e7] Ne7-Ng6-Be7 next.}) 6... e6 {this is an Advanced French, where Black doesn't have the Bc8 problem...} 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. O-O cxd4 ({not} 8... Nge7 $6 {because of} 9. dxc5 {and it could become more or less interesting for White.}) 9. cxd4 Nge7 10. Nc3 Nf5 $11 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Be7-00 next simply.} 11. g4 $6 {[%csl Rg4] has been tried in some games, but g4 is a weakness.} Nfe7 $15 {[%csl Rg1,Rg4][%cal Gh7h5,Ge8c8] h5 next, and we can continue with long castle.}) (4. Nc3 {This move is interesting against 3...Bf5, but not against 3...c5. There are 125 games in this position, mostly played online, and my explanation is simple: 4.Nc3 is often just a premove, as White usually expects 3...Bf5! :)} Nc6 (4... e6 {is another good option. After} 5. Nf3 Nc6 $132 {[%csl Rc3] we play a French without a tempo, but White has a seriously misplaced Nc3.}) 5. dxc5 {only move for White to maintain the equality.} (5. Nf3 $6 Bg4 $15 {[%csl Rc3] Nc3 clearly misplaced.}) (5. Bb5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 e6 $36 {[%cal Gg8e7] Nge7 next. I am not sure that White equalizes.}) 5... e6 6. Nf3 Bxc5 7. Bd3 f6 $5 {rare but effective. Black is just fine.} 8. Qe2 fxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Qxe5 Nf6 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc5d6] 00-Bd6 next.}) (4. Be3 $6 {extremely bad from the positional perspective, because the bishop on d4 will be misplaced.} cxd4 5. Bxd4 {[%csl Rd4]} Nc6 $36 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8h6,Gh6f5] e6-Nh6-Nf5 next.}) 4... Nc6 5. c3 e6 {If White is willing to do anything—even placing his knight misplaced on e2—just to reach a French-like position, then we are more than happy to go for it!} (5... Bf5 $6 {Black's most common continuation, but it's a mistake!} 6. dxc5 $1 Nxe5 (6... e6 7. b4 $14) 7. Ng3 $14) 6. g3 {only playable option for White.} (6. Be3 $6 Qb6 7. Qd2 f6 $15 {Black is already better.}) (6. a3 f6 $1 $15 {[%csl Gf6]}) (6. Nd2 cxd4 7. cxd4 f6 {[%csl Gf6] as you have already seen, f6 is a typical idea for us.} 8. Nf3 fxe5 9. dxe5 Qc7 $132 {easier to play it for Black.}) 6... cxd4 {better to play it now because White is forced to capture with the pawn.} ({White has a better version if we start with the immediate} 6... f6 7. exf6 Qxf6 8. Bg2 cxd4 (8... Nge7 9. dxc5 $14) 9. Nxd4 $1 $14) 7. cxd4 f6 {the simplest solution.} 8. Bh3 $1 {engine's first move.} (8. exf6 Qxf6 $1 $36 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg8e7,Ge7f5] Nge7-Nf5 next, and White should be precise to equalize.}) (8. f4 Be7 $132 {[%cal Gg8h6,Ge8g8] Nh6-00 next and no problems.}) 8... fxe5 9. dxe5 Bb4+ {the simplest.} (9... Nxe5 {is also not bad, but after} 10. O-O $44 {White has full compensation.}) 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2 (11. Qxd2 $2 Nxe5 $17 {[%cal Ge5f3]}) 11... Nxe5 12. O-O Nf6 {Now White can at best equalize.} 13. Nf4 Qd6 {and everything will liquidate after the logical moves} 14. Re1 O-O 15. Qe2 Nf7 16. Bxe6 Bxe6 17. Qxe6 Qb4 18. Nf1 Qxb2 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Qxd5 $11 {We can conclude that if White doesn't continue with 4.c3, 4.Nf3, or 4.dxc5, we immediately get an excellent position, which is also very easy to play for us.} *

